<HEADLINE> Chilean Ambassador Says to Settle Pinochet Row Amicably </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Chilean ambassador to Britain
Mario Artaza said Tuesday that his government could try to settle
amicably the current argument on extraditing former Chilean
president Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to BBC radio early Tuesday, Artaza said that a Chilean
specialist on international law was travelling to Britain for
talks with British Foreign Office over the Santiago government's
contention that Pinochet has diplomatic immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
"This (diplomatic immunity) is something we will continue to
discuss. They will try to reach a conclusion that will save faces
for everyone involved," Artaza said.
</P>
<P>
British police arrested Pinochet, who is in London for medical
treatment, over the weekend for alleged involvement in the torture
and murder of 79 Spanish citizens in the 1970s
</P>
<P>
Artaza noted that Chile and Britain would try to settle the row
amicably but he questioned why Pinochet, a former president,
should be questioned in Spain.
</P>
<P>
"Why should he (Pinochet) be answering to a court in Spain for
crimes that allegedly he committed in Chile?" Artaza asked.
</P>
<P>
Early Monday, Pinochet, who enjoys immunity from prosecution in
Chile as a lifelong senator, said that he was confident of
successfully opposing attempts to extradite him from Britain to
Spain.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued Monday on his behalf said: "Any attempt to
extradite him (Pinochet) from the United Kingdom will be
resolutely opposed. Both he and his family are confident of
success." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
