<HEADLINE> Iranian Party's Election Rally Ends in Clashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Clashes erupted Tuesday
afternoon at the first rally held by the moderate Party of
Constructive Executives of Iran (CEI) for the election of the
Experts Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Police intervened and there are no reports of casualties.
</P>
<P>
A dozens of CEI's supporters rushed into physical fighting
with several hard-liners, who upheld pictures of the Iranian
supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei to disturb the speech of
the CEI Secretary General Gholamhussein Karbaschi.
</P>
<P>
An audience of 7,000 audience was angered by the behavior of
the hard-liners and shouted slogans against them at the rally
held in the basketball hall of the Shahid Shiroudi Sports Complex
in central Tehran.
</P>
<P>
They also shouted slogans supporting the moderate President
Mohammad Khatami and Karbaschi, former Tehran mayor, who was
ousted in July by the conservatives on charge of embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
"Khatami, Khatami, We support you Khatami, Khatami, We love
you" the crowd chanted, "Karbaschi Hero, Iran's Amir Kabir (a
famous Iranian reformist in the 19th century)."
</P>
<P>
The clashes continued for about 20 minutes and a dozen of
policemen with masks and sticks entered the hall and dispersed
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
At the rally, Karbaschi urged the Iranian nation to
participate in the election for the Experts Assembly on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Although there were some problems with the procedure to
screen the qualifications of the candidates (by the Guardians
Council), the people should turn out vehemently to exercise
their rights," the CEI secretary general said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the election of the Experts Assembly has special
importance in the country since it is the Experts Assembly that
determines the country's supreme leader and review the leader's
performances.
</P>
<P>
According to Iran's constitution, the 86-seat Expert Assembly
also has the right to dismiss the leader if it believes that the
leader has not carried out his duties.
</P>
<P>
The conservative-dominated Guardians Council, empowered to
screen the qualifications of candidates for elections in the
country, was accused of taking side while carrying out its duties.
</P>
<P>
"If anyone has protest, he should go to cast his vote
in the election," Karbaschi said, "this is the right way to
express one's protest, it is not right to boycott the
election."
</P>
<P>
After some of their prominent candidates were rejected by the
Guardians Council, the left-wing or moderate factions refused to
announce their lists of candidates for the election. Some
candidates from the left-wing factions have even withdrawn from
the election campaigns in a protest to the screening policy of
the Guardians Council.
</P>
<P>
However, the CEI, well-known as a moderate party, insisted
that the people should perform their duties and show their
presence in the country's political arena. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
