<HEADLINE> Greece Warns European Commission Not to Release Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Greece warned Tuesday that
Athens would be forced to have recourse to the European Court of
Justice if the European Commission did not change its proposals on
the release of community funds for neighboring Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The warning was issued by Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros
Pangalos in a letter to his Austrian counterpart Wolfgang
Schuessel.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Pangalos strongly criticized the commission's
attempt to release the European Union (EU) funds for Turkey, and
asked Schuessel to intervene to prevent the adoption of the
commission proposals on the funds release, which Greece considered
to be legally unfounded.
</P>
<P>
The attempt was contrary to decisions taken at the EU summit in
Cardiff, Britain, he said, adding that a mistaken approach on the
part of the European Commission would in the future create many
problems.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, Greece for years has been blocking about 405
million U.S. dollars of EU money destined for Turkey, which Greece
accuses of not meeting standards regarding human rights,
territorial claims and other issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
