<HEADLINE> Museveni, Mandela Talk About Congo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni had consultative talks about Congo Crisis with his South
African counterpart Nelson Mandela in Pretoria during his
three-day working visit.
</P>
<P>
Museveni returned home Tuesday afternoon after the talks in
South Africa, a press release from the President's Office said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The day-long confidential talks between Museveni and Mandela
have focused on the widening conflict in the Democratic Republic
of Congo (DRC) as well as the situation in the region in general,
said the press release.
</P>
<P>
It was said that the talks in Pretoria were part of a series
of negotiations Mandela planned to hold over the next week with
key players in the war in the vast central African country.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in South Africa, the Ugandan president also
had meetings with the South African Defense Minister Joe Modise
and Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Aziz Pohad, it added.
</P>
<P>
Before going to Pretoria, Museveni had met Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi and Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa in Kenyan
capital Nairobi Sunday, calling for the peaceful withdrawal of
all foreign troops from the war-torn Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
Mandela has also called for all-inclusive peace talks between
Congolese President Laurent Kabila and the rebels, but Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe allegedly pushed for a military solution.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the situation became more complicated after
the rebels recently took over the strategic town of Kindu which
is a major access to the mining areas in the east and south of
Congo. Kabila had tried to use this base to launch attacks on the
rebels who had occupied large tracts of land in eastern Congo.
</P>
<P>
Museveni was accompanied to in his South Africa visit by his
Minister of State for Foreign Affairs in charge of Regional
Cooperation Amama Mbabazi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
