<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN: Over 800 Million People Suffer from Chronic Hunger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 20 (Xinhua) -- More than 800 million
people suffer from chronic hunger or malnutrition, and 200 million
of them are children, U.N. Deputy Secretary-General Louise
Frechette said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Frechette, delivering the speech on behalf of Secretary-General
Kofi Annan who is currently on a visit to Japan, made the remarks
as the United Nations marked the World Food Day, which falls on
October 16 each year, at its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
"The short-and long-term effects of hunger are well known," she
said, "People's capacity for growth and daily activity are
stunned. Hungry people cannot fulfill their human potential as
individuals, or as a society."
</P>
<P>
"This has devastating consequences both in economic and
political terms," she said.
</P>
<P>
"The world has enough food, as well as the technology and the
knowhow, to feed everyone," she said, "What is needed is a
collective political will."
</P>
<P>
A first step is to recognize fully the critical contribution
to food security that is made by women -- and to work to remove
the obstacles they face in carrying out their role, she said.
</P>
<P>
This year's theme for the World Food Day is "Women feed the
world."
</P>
<P>
In the face of poverty, natural disasters and war, it is the
resilience and ingenuity of women that enables families and
communities to survive, she said.
</P>
<P>
It is hard to do justice to the daily struggle of rural women
and the multitude of obstacles and discriminatory practices they
face in accomplishing their daily workload, she said.
</P>
<P>
"What is even harder is the opportunities lost for growth and
development for many women, their families, and society.
Agricultural development policies still do not reflect the needs
of women adequately," she added.
</P>
<P>
The Tuesday activity to mark the World Food Day was presided
over by Didier Opertti, president of the 53rd General Assembly
session.
</P>
<P>
In his message for the World Food Day this year, Annan said,
"Every year, World Food Day reminds us of a tragic reality --
that the war against hunger and is still being fought."
</P>
<P>
In 1980, the General Assembly called for the observance of
the World Food Day for the first time on October 16, 1981 and
annually thereafter to heighten public awareness of the problem
of hunger in the world and to encourage attention to food
production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
