<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pressure for Rate Cut in Britain Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 20 (Xinhua) - Evidence of economic downturn and
fall of business confidence in Britain will step up the pressure
on the Bank of England's Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) for
further cut in rates, business leaders said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Adair Turner, CBI (Confederation of British Industry)
Director-General said at a press conference this afternoon that
business confidence was now at its lowest point since the end of
1992.
</P>
<P>
Export confidence was at its lowest point for almost 10 years,
he said, adding it's up to MPC to take right step to prevent the
threat of recession.
</P>
<P>
Turner argued that Britain was now suffering from deflation,
not inflation. He said that CBI found little change in
manufacturing pay deals over the year, which suggests there is
little inflationary pressure coming from the UK's industrial
sector.
</P>
<P>
Consumer confidence has also shown its biggest slide since the
depths of the last recession but there is no sign of a let-up in
the urge to spend, says a survey out Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Business Strategies quarterly consumer index shows the
balance of people feeling confident about the economy has slipped
by 16 percentage points to 11 percent in the three months to
October - the sharpest decline since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Melanie Lansbury, author of the survey, said: "People are
clearly worried about the coming year, and this is hardly
surprising with announcement of job losses becoming a regular
news..." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder's Government to Seek Better Control of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October 20 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor-elect Gerhard
Schroeder said Tuesday that his new government would seek more
better international coordinations to improve the controls of
global financial markets in order to help prevent global economic
crises.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference after his Social Democratic Party
(SPD) and the Greens signed a deal to form Germany's first
center-left coalition government in 16 years, Schroeder announced
that one of the first tasks of his finance minister will be to
seek more cooperations with partner countries to improve the
controls of international financial markets and banks.
</P>
<P>
Oskar Lafontaine, the designated finance minister, said earlier
that the new government would forge a financial markets' stability
pact with France and Britain, including a drive for linked
exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
The plan of the new government represents a major policy shift
from the conservative government of Chancellor Helmut Kohl, which
favors a more free-market approach.
</P>
<P>
Political observers suggest that the change of government in
Bonn would provide the opportunity for the large majority of
leftist governments in Europe to move together to pursue a more
interventist policy.
</P>
<P>
As another reflection of the policy change in Bonn, Schroeder
indicated Tuesday that he would be willing to see the German
central bank, the Bundesbank, follow the example of the U.S.
Federal Reserve Board to cut interest rates in order to spur
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The politically independent Bundesbank has so far resisted any
rates cut and say that this does provide the right answer to the
actual problems faced by the world economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
