<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Starts Six-Day Military Exercise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus started the annual
military exercise "Nikiforos '98" on Tuesday, with the
participation of the Greek Armed Forces.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the reservists who enlisted for the six-day
manoeuvres, Defense Minister Yiannakis Omirou said the National
Guard's annual exercise gives the message that the Cyprus people
firmly support the defense of the island.
</P>
<P>
This, he said, is the main objective of Cyprus and Greece in
the context of the joint defense pact between the two countries,
signed in November 1993.
</P>
<P>
Under the pact, Greece will provide military assistance to
Cyprus in case the government-controlled southern part of the
island is attacked.
</P>
<P>
Omirou said this year's exercise aims at "training the whole of
the armed forces, with emphasis on the reservists in war
situations."
</P>
<P>
All National Guard fighting services will participate in the
exercise, joined by Greek warplanes and navy ships, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Omirou also stressed that the message of the manoeuvres is to
let Turkey know of "the political, military, and economic cost she
will pay" in case of any attempt against the Republic of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier announcement, the major part of the
exercise will take place in the southeastern district of Larnaca
with the use of live ammunition. The Greek warplanes are expected
to land at the "Andreas Papandreou" air base near the southwestern
town of Paphos, which was put to use -- only by Greek warplanes --
last February.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the participation of Greek warplanes
and ships may again heighten tension in this Eastern
Mediterranean island, which has remained divided since 1974 when
Turkey laned its troops and took over the northern third in the
wake of an abortive pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Last year, after participation of Greek naval and air forces in
the same type annual exercise in Cyprus, Turkey sent military
aircraft and warships to the Turkish Cypriot-controlled northern
part of the island for retaliation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus to protect
the Turkish Cypriots, who declared unilaterally in 1983 a
breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by
Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
