<HEADLINE> Russia not to Consider Union with Yugoslavia Now </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Russia at present is hardly
to consider the implementation of making a union with Yugoslavia,
Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said at a
briefing here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmanin said the idea of Yugoslavia joining the
Russia-Belarus Union, put forward during the trip of members of
the State Duma to that country, is the reflection of friendly
feelings of the Russian and Yugoslav nations for each other.
</P>
<P>
On the Russian-Estonian relations, the spokesman said Russia
always called for development of the relations, which had recently
shown promising signs of positive change.
</P>
<P>
"We expect that this interaction with the new leadership of the
Estonian foreign ministry... will be hopeful to consolidation of
these shifts into a steady tendency," Rakhmanin said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed "indignation and extreme concern" about the Monday
explosion in Beer-Sheba, Israel, in which dozens of people were
wounded.
</P>
<P>
Rakhmanin noted that "The bloody extremist sortie had the
evident purpose of escalating tension in Palestinian-Israeli
relations, provoking armed confrontation and thus torpedoing the
process of political settlement."
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the relations between Iran and Turkey, he said
Russia resolutely stands for maintaining the territorial integrity
of the countries with a Kurdish population, including Iran and
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Moscow is convinced that "the Kurdish problem cannot be
resolved by the use of force but a way out may be found only
through a political settlement."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Georgia's relations with its breakaway
Abkhazia province, the spokesman welcomed the Athens meeting
between the two sides. Delegations of Georgia and Abkhazia met in
Athens, Greece, on October 16-18 to generate trust-building
measures.
</P>
<P>
"The fact of the Athens meeting doubtlessly has a positive
meaning for reduction of the level of tension between the sides,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Rakhmanin, the meeting adopted a resolution which
laid down Georgia-Abkhazia accords on trust-building measures for
safe return of Georgian refugees to Abkhazia, economic, cultural
and humanitarian cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
