<HEADLINE> 24 Coup Convicts Executed in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-four officers and
soldiers convicted of involvement in the May 1997 coup have been
executed in Sierra Leone, reports from Freetown said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The execution were carried out Monday at about 4.30 p.m local
time, and were witnessed by about 200 people.
</P>
<P>
It is the first death sentences carried out in connection with
the coup in 1997 that overthrew elected President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah, who was reinstated last March by the Nigerian-led west
African peacekeeping force ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
The 24 persons executed Monday were convicted of treason by a
Freetown court last week.
</P>
<P>
Another 10 persons, all officers, were convicted at the same
time, but have reportedly had their sentences commuted to life
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the trial of the second batch of civilian
collaborators with the military junta ended in Freetown Monday,
with 16 of the 20 accused convicted of treason, murder and a
sC99j$KWV$M..HW.H3reed.
</P>
<P>
Another accused, Foday Sankoh, who was leader of the rebel
United Revolutionary Front, reportedly died in detention, but it
could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh had been fighting against consecutive Sierra Leonean
governments since early 1990s. He was detained in Nigeria in
1997 and transferred to the Kabbah government for trial earlier
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
