<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov Stresses More State Control Over Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov on Tuesday stressed the need for more state regulation in
pulling the country out of the economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"The theory that the market will resolve everything on its own
has not justified itself," said Primakov, addressing a conference
of the country's business leaders.
</P>
<P>
"Before real market relations establish themselves in the
country, the state must assume regulatory functions, ensure order
in the country," Primakov told participants of the Ninth Congress
of the Russian Union of Industrialists and Entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
Primakov, who took over as prime minister a little over a month
ago, said his government would support domestic producers through
its fiscal, tax and social policies, rather than offering more
credits.
</P>
<P>
"By merely pumping money (into the industrial sector), we will
never achieve economic growth," the Itar-Tass news agency quoted
Primakov as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would strive to cut value-added tax and
profit tax and other measures to ease the tax burden of the
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Arkady Volsky, the union's president, praised the Primakov
cabinet's moves.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time in the years of reform, there is a light at
the end of the tunnel, the light of hope, not of a mourning lamp,"
Volsky said.
</P>
<P>
He noted particularly the government's measures to enhance the
state's role in the economy, Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Primakov's speech was also well received by Gennady Zyuganov,
leader of the Communist faction in the State Duma, or lower house
of parliament.
</P>
<P>
He claimed, based on speeches at the Tuesday conference of
industrialists and entrepreneurs, that the government was
abandoning the economic policies pursued by its former reformist
governments, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said proposals to cut energy prices, transport charges and
taxes and to improve tax collection had particularly impressed
him.
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party and the People's Patriotic Union have been
demanding such measures for the last five years, Zyuganov said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Primakov told reporters after his meeting at
the Kremlin with President Boris Yeltsin that if a decision on
monetary emission, or printing money, is taken, the emission "will
be very small."
</P>
<P>
He admitted that printing more money is dangerous but "when the
money in circulation has a backing, there is very little danger or
no danger at all," Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Chairman Viktor Gerashchenko, who also took part
in the meeting, said that "not emission, but an enlargement of the
monetary base" guaranteed by the gold and foreign reserves" should
be discussed.
</P>
<P>
"The restoration of trust in banks and active involvement of
the population's ruble savings in the economy are the most
important things," he said.
</P>
<P>
The moves for stronger role of the state and printing of more
money have worried the West, which argues that the steps would
fuel hyperinflation and could eventually result in social chaos.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of the International Monetary Fund was to discuss
on Wednesday with the Russian government the possible release of a
4.3 billion U.S. dollar loan, the second tranche of the IMF's
stabilization package to Russia, Deputy Finance Minister Oleg
Vyugin said.
</P>
<P>
However, Alexander Shokhin, who briefly handled Moscow's
negotiations with international lending agencies before quitting
the Primakov cabinet, said Tuesday that "money from the
International Monetary Fund should not be expected" before
January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
