<HEADLINE> Clinton Invites Hussein to Join Mideast Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has
invited Jordan's King Hussein to join the Palestinian-Israeli
summit held in the U.S. to cash in on his good ties with both
sides to ensure its success, a senior official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The king will arrive at the Wye Plantation near Washington
late Tuesday evening and is expected to meet Clinton, Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu separately, said Minister of Information Nasir Judeh
at a weekly press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said the king's meetings with these leaders are part of the
 ongoing efforts aimed at hammering out a Palestinian-Israeli
agreement on a U.S. peace proposal which calls on Israel to
withdraw from 13.1 percent of the West Bank in order to reactivate
the long-stalled Palestinian-Israeli peace process.
</P>
<P>
The king will use his good offices with both Arafat and
Netanyahu to bridge their gap on the U.S. proposal, Judeh added.
</P>
<P>
Hussein has been staying at a Minnesota clinic for some three
months to treat cancer.
</P>
<P>
The Wye Plantation summit entered its sixth day on Tuesday
while the gap between the two sides was still unbridged over
some major issues.
</P>
<P>
The summit was proposed by the U.S. who pinned high hopes on
the Palestinians and Israel to reach an agreement and reactivate
their peace process which has been deadlocked since March 1997.
</P>
<P>
Jordan, who signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1994, has been
maintaining frequent high-level contacts with both parties.
</P>
