<HEADLINE> Red Crescent Official Attacked by Gunmen in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Unidentified gunmen have
launched an armed attack on the secretary-general of the Somali
Red Crescent Society (SRCS) in north Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The attack took place Monday night when Nur Hassan Hussein
(Nur Addeh) was presiding a meeting in the residence of Dr. Mina
Hassan, the director of the Keysaney Hospital run by the
International Committee of Red Cross (ICRC).
</P>
<P>
According to the neighbors, more than 20 heavily-armed men
carrying rocket-propelled grenades and assault rifles attacked
the house of Mina.
</P>
<P>
The neighbors also said that the heavily-armed guards at the
residence defended the area from the perpetrators and captured
two of the raiders with their guns.
</P>
<P>
At least two people were wounded, one of them a bystander,
during the attack which terrified the residential area of Shibbis
district in the capital.
</P>
<P>
There were no attacks or counter-attacks between the two sides
Tuesday and the situation seems to return to the normal.
</P>
<P>
There are no identity of the attackers. However, the
neighbors said they recognized some of the attackers, describing
them as the same kidnappers of the 10 ICRC aid workers who were
abducted in north Mogadishu in mid-April this year.
</P>
<P>
The Somali Red Crescent Society collaborates with the ICRC as
its partner in the capital in arranging or fulfilling several
humanitarian businesses on behalf of the ICRC.
</P>
<P>
The reason for raid is not known, either. But sources close
to the gunmen said the action had something to do with the
released ICRC staff members after their captivity of nine days in
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to a source, Nur Addeh who just returned to
Mogadishu this week had promised to pay the gunmen more money
when he returned, but he failed to keep his words.
</P>
<P>
There is no word as yet from the SRCS secretary-general or his
agency over the attack.
</P>
<P>
This has not been the first such attack against Nur Addeh in
Mogadishu. There was another attack against him at the residence
of Mogadishu's former mayor, Ali Ugas Abdulle, in Karan district
of north Mogadishu, which had been foiled by the guards.
</P>
<P>
There has been no official settlement over the issue between
Nur Addeh and the gunmen allegedly seeking him for money.
</P>
<P>
However, latest reports said that the elders from both sides
are busy trying to solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The abduction of the 10 ICRC staff members in Mogadishu led to
the departure of all the international relief workers of the
non-governmental organizations (NGOs) operating in Mogadishu as a
sign expressing solidarity with the ICRC.
</P>
<P>
The Somali capital still lingers with the humanitarian crises
resulting from the departure of the international NGOs from
Mogadishu after the abduction of the ICRC staff members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
