<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Principles on Internal Displacement Urged to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Chen Cailin)
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 20 (Xinhua) -- A two-day workshop on
internal displacement in Africa ended Tuesday evening with a call
for the wide dissemination and application in Africa of the
guiding principles on internal displacement.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was jointly organized by the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) and the United Nations High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) to focus attention on internal displacement in
Africa and identify ways to improve the response at the regional
level.
</P>
<P>
According to the OAU statistics, there are about 20 million
internally displaced persons in Africa.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held after the workshop, OAU Assistant
Secretary-General for Political Affairs Daniel Antonio said that
the situation of internal displacement in Africa "is still
serious."
</P>
<P>
On promoting the application in Africa of the Guilding
Principles on internal displacement which were presented to the
UN Commission on Human Rights this year, the workshop said that
these principles set forth the rights of the internally displaced
for protection and assistance and the obligations of governments
and insurgent groups toward these populations.
</P>
<P>
They serve as a valuable tool for addressing more effectively
the crisis of internal displacement in Africa, said the
participants.
</P>
<P>
Referring to exploring the role of regional and sub-regional
organizations in dealing with internal displacement, the workshop
encouraged them to develop a more active role with the internally
displaced, especially when there is a lack of any international
agency specificly responsible for the internally displaced.
</P>
<P>
The workshop called on the OAU as well sub-regional bodies to
actively disseminate and apply the principles, using them as a
basis for advocacy and monitoring.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from international organizations, regional
bodies, non-governmental organizations and research institutions
engaged with internally displaced populations attended the
workshop.
</P>
<P>
Participants also made recommendations on internal
displacement in Africa to the OAU Ministerial Meeting on
Refugees, Returnees and Displaced Persons which will be held in
Khartoum, capital of the Sudan in December this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Women Comprise 1/3 of Employed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Census '96 results released Tuesday show that 3.5 million of
the country's 9.1 million employed citizens were female, compared
to 5.5 million men.
</P>
<P>
Of the 4.7 million unemployed, 2.1 million were men, and 2.6
million women.
</P>
<P>
The census results reveal that more women than men were in
unskilled occupations, and they earned less.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-seven percent of black and 41 percent of colored women
were in unskilled occupations, while 50 percent of white men were
in managerial, professional or technical occupations.
</P>
<P>
Forty-eight percent of employed black women earn 500 Rand (88
U.S. Dollars) or less per month, while 65 percent of white men
earn more than 3,000 Rand (526 Dollars) a month.
</P>
<P>
However, nearly as many women as men have after-school
qualifications, 646,000 compared to 649,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
