<HEADLINE> Podesta Appointed White House Chief of Staff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday appointed John Podesta as his new White House chief of
staff, effective November 1, replacing Erskine Bowles, who may run
for governor in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
In a Rose Garden ceremony, Clinton described Podesta as having
a "tough hide, a dry wit, a lot of patience in dealing with the
president, hard-worn wisdom and a genuine compassion for improving
this nation."
</P>
<P>
Podesta, 49, has been deputy chief of staff for the past two
years. Prior to that he was a visiting law professor at Georgetown
University, and a top aide to Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle,
a South Dakota Democrat. Earlier, he was a senior policy adviser
to Clinton. He also was Clinton's staff secretary.
</P>
<P>
"He knows how the White House works," said Clinton. "But even
more importantly, he knows why the White House ought to work and
for whom every single one of us does work. He entered public
service for the right reasons and he has certainly stayed there
for the right reasons."
</P>
<P>
Over the years Podesta has been constructing a communications
strategy for dealing with various controversies that have erupted,
including the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
Bowles had planned to resign earlier in the year but stayed on
to help Clinton with the Lewinsky matter. He has been considering
a possible run for governor in his home state of North Carolina
in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
