<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 20 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Turkey signed a pact on Tuesday to enhance
trade exchange and expand economic links between them, Egypt's
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Goweili who signed
the deal said the pact included an agreement on participation in
exhibitions to be held in both countries, and an exchange of
visits by business people.
</P>
<P>
Signing for Turkey was visiting Deputy Trade Minister Yavuz
Ege, who unveiled interest in reaching a free trade agreement with
Egypt to enhance their trade which he said was steadily increasing
by around 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish official, leading a delegation of businessmen, put
at 650 million U.S. dollars the value of trade exchange between
the two countries last year, against 550 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An Egyptian-Greek business symposium will be held late
next week in the Egyptian resort town of Alexandria for promoting
trade and economic cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Greek Ambassador to Cairo George Assimacopoulos said Tuesday
that a 50-member delegation from Greece would arrive in Egypt next
week to attend the symposium which runs from October 28 through
November 1.
</P>
<P>
He added that the delegation, composed of business people and
Greek officials, would explore with their Egyptian counterparts
opportunities for launching joint ventures as well.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, the fifth of its kind, is organized by the
Egyptian-Greek Businessmen Society. Egyptian-Greek trade exchange
reached 969 million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's trade deficit in the first seven months of
this year was down by 2.9 percent, compared with that during the
same period of last year, the semi-official Jordan Times Tuesday
quoted a Central Bank of Jordan report as saying.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit during the first seven months of this year
was 878.8 million Jordanian dinars (1,241.2 million U.S. dollars)
and that during the same period of last year was 904.9 million
dinars (1,278.1 million dollars), the report said, while not
giving the reason for the decrease.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan expects 100,000 tourists from the United States
to come to the kingdom this year, a 16 percent increase over that
of last year, Minister of Tourism and Antiquities Akil Beltaji
said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Altogether 86,000 U.S. tourists came to Jordan in 1997, said
Beltaji in a press statement issued upon his return from a trip to
the U.S. and France to promote Jordan's sightseeing sites.
</P>
</TEXT>
