<HEADLINE> FM: Cyprus to Ask Egypt to Exert Influence on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus will ask Egypt to exert
its influence on Turkey in relation with the Cyprus question,
Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the Larnaca Airport before his departure
for Cairo for a two-day official visit.
</P>
<P>
"We will certainly ask of our friendly neighbor, Egypt, to
exert its influence on Turkey, just as we ask all those who have
the capability to do that," Kasoulides told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The minister said he will discuss with his Egyptian
counterpart Amr Moussa "issues of mutual interest, developments in
the Middle East peace process, the problem between Turkey and
Syria and of course the Cyprus question."
</P>
<P>
"We lay particular emphasis on our relations with all the
countries of the region and specifically Egypt, with whom we
maintain friendly ties even before the Cyprus Republic was
established," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides noted that problems in the region "are common
problems for all of us and we are interested in seeing peace and
stability in this region."
</P>
<P>
"In this context, it is wise to exchange ideas, particularly
with a friendly country, which is playing one of the leading
roles in the region for what is happening around us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the role of Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in
the disputes between Turkey and Syria, Kasoulides said "every
political personality that can exert influence on Turkey is
obviously a positive thing for us."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of harboring Turkish outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party, but Damascus has denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has recently shuttled between Turkey and Syria to try
to persuade the two sides to solve their disputes through dialog.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release here Tuesday, during his visit,
Kasoulides will convey a personal message from Cypriot President
Glafcos Clerides to Mubarak. 
</P>
