<HEADLINE> Taliban Promises to Punish Killers of Iranian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 20 (Xinhua) -- U.N. special envoy on Afghan
affairs Lakhdar Brahimi said here Tuesday that the Afghan Taliban
militia promised to identify and punish those responsible for
killing eight Iranian diplomats and a reporter in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi made the remarks upon his arrival from Pakistan after
paying a visit to Kandahar, the Taliban's headquarters in
southern Afghanistan, the Iranian official news agency IRNA
reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Taliban also asked him to convey the group's
regret over the bitter incident to the Iranian government and the
families of the killed Iranians.
</P>
<P>
Taliban troops reportedly stormed Iran's consulate in Mazari
Sharif in northern Afghanistan on August 8 and killed eight
Iranian diplomats and an IRNA reporter in the consulate.
</P>
<P>
Iran was angered by the move and massed more than 200,000
troops on its eastern borders with Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to defuse the tensions between Iran and the
Taliban, Brahimi paid a shuttle visit to Iran, Pakistan and
Afghanistan in recent weeks. He returned to Tehran after the
Taliban released 26 Iranians arrested in Afghanistan and announced
readiness to talk with Iran.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. envoy did not give more details about his
talks with the Taliban leaders, but said that he would make
efforts to bring all the Afghan belligerent parties to
negotiations and to establish peace in the war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Receiving Brahimi at the airport, Iranian Deputy Foreign
Minister for Asia-Pacific Affairs Mohsen Amin-Zadeh voiced
Tehran's readiness to cooperate with the U.N. to bring peace to
Afghanistan. 
</P>
