<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Soar on Renewed Hopes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- European stock markets pushed
higher to close well up Tuesday on a host of factors ranging from
rises in Tokyo and New York, a stronger dollar to takeover
speculation and reports that rates in Emu member states would
converge at 3.3 percent rather than something higher.
</P>
<P>
Expectations of lower U.K. interest rates, together with a
bullish performance on Wall Street brought the FTSE 100 up by
174.4 points to end at 5251.9, after reaching a session best of
5267.9 in late trade.
</P>
<P>
Second-liners continued their solid, if unspectacular trend,
with the FTSE 250 rising 57 points to 4630.8.
</P>
<P>
A firm financial sector helped the index power ahead, as the
sector extended Monday's gains amid talk that Deutsche Bank was
mulling a takeover of the U.S. Bankers Trust.
</P>
<P>
"The banks did really well on Wall Street yesterday and a lot
of people who were short came rushing back in today," said one
trader. Only a handfull of top shares missed out on the party.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares moved ahead as increased investor
confidence fuelled a broad-based technical recovery. The leading
Dax index closed 137 points up at 4,595.
</P>
<P>
Dealers pointed to an absence of bad news, which seemed enough
to spur buy orders in a jittery market.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector soared on unconfirmed media reports that
Deutsche Bank is in preliminary takeover talks with Bankers Trust
of the U.S. Should the deal be agreed, it would be the largest
takeover of a U.S. bank by an overseas bank. There was also some
renewed optimism in the car sector.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French shares rose, too, on the back of a firmer
dollar and Wall Street's bullish lead. The Cac 40 closed up at
3,492, that's 97 points higher.
</P>
<P>
"Although the market is languishing in the absence of
market-moving news, the Cac 40 index is still heading for its
eighth consecutive rise," said a trader at Oddo brokerage house.
</P>
