<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola in Severe Economic Austerity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Angola is facing grave
financial situation this year with serious current account
deficit, great difficulty to service its foreign debt as a result
of sharp fall in the prices of crude oil on the international
market.
</P>
<P>
The Angola National Bank (its central bank) estimated in a
document issued Tuesday that the country's current account
deficit will reach 806 million U.S. Dollars this year, which is
about 12 percent of Angola's gross domestic products (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The main reason for this, said the document, is that the price
of crude oil, the country's major export product, is down by 35
percent on the international market although its export has been
on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Angola is the second largest oil producing country in Africa
with a current daily output of 750,000 barrels. Oil export
earns 90 percent of the country's foreign currency. However,
the price for crude oil has fallen from 18 Dollars per barrel in
1997 to less than 12 Dollars at present.
</P>
<P>
Consequently, said the document, Angola finds itself unable to
service a batch of foreign debt due this year and this delay in
debt servicing has in turn made foreign financial institutions
refuse to provide new loans.
</P>
<P>
The national bank estimated a 674-million-Dollar deficit in
balance of payments, a shortfall of 128 million Dollars in
foreign exchange reserve and an accumulated 546 million Dollars
in foreign debt for the southern African country this year.
</P>
<P>
The bank believed that the current financial situation in
Angola has brought great harm to the country's credibility on the
international financial market.
</P>
<P>
If the international price of crude oil cannot improve in the
recent future, the financial situation in the country will
further deteriorate, noted the document.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
