<HEADLINE> Actions Urged Against Foreign Workers in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) Jamil Al-Hujailan made an alarming
call Tuesday for GCC states to solve the issue of foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
Al-Hujailan, who is attending the 15th meeting of the GCC
labor and social affairs ministerial council starting here
earlier Tuesday, said the problem of the expatriate workers
implicates dangerous impact at the social, economic and political
levels, and become much more complicated in the future, the Kuwait
News Agency (Kuna) reported.
</P>
<P>
"Dealing with all these (foreign) communities, particularly if
their number increases in the future, will be extremely
difficult," Al-Hujailan said.
</P>
<P>
Voicing concern on the expatriates' impact on the Gulf social
customs and traditions, he said "the sole solution is replacing
foreign laborers with nationals."
</P>
<P>
The GCC chief confirmed that the GCC Higher Council, which
comprises top leaders of the Gulf states, has decided to make the
issue a permanent topic in the agendas of GCC ministerial meetings.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the GCC labor ministers have concluded that
the private sector is one of the main parties involved in this
problem.
</P>
<P>
Al-Hujailan urged private companies to employ nationals instead
of foreigners.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The number of foreign workers in the Gulf region is estimated
at 5 million, approximately one fifth of the 26 million
population of the GCC states, Kuna said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
