<HEADLINE> Zambian Striking Teachers Urged to Return to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Education Minister
Godfrey Miyanda Tuesday called on the striking teachers to return
to work and give the government and teachers' unions a chance to
negotiate.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda said the on-going strike is without the blessings of
the government nor the teachers' unions.
</P>
<P>
The strike is not only illegal but also in bad faith, he said,
adding the teachers had been addressed earlier by President
Frederick Chiluba, who announced the commencement of
negotiations and the lifting of the wage freeze next year.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda urged the teachers to exercise wisdom and patience to give
the government a chance to address the issues.
</P>
<P>
The minister dismissed the teachers' demand for better
conditions of service and salaries as unrealistic and
unattainable.
</P>
<P>
Better conditions or salaries cannot be implemented this year
and therefore there must be a different agenda for the boycott,
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the problems of teachers have beset
his ministry for years and a solution can be found through
sitting down together and talk.
</P>
<P>
The strike has been harmful to the children, said Miyanda, who
called on the teachers not to fall prey to what he described as
those who "fly by night" and have taken advantage of this situation
to cause confusion among teachers.
</P>
<P>
The teachers went on strike last week demanding a review of
their conditions of service and an increase in monthly salaries
currently pegged at 100,000 Kwacha (about 50 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
