<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-20 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish FM: Syria Pledges to Shut Down PKK Camps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Syria Tuesday pledged to shut
down camps of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) on its
territory and in the Syrian-controlled Bekka Valley, Turkish
Foreign Minister Ismail Cem said here.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed by high-ranking diplomatic and
military officials of Turkey and Syria, Damascus also agreed not
to allow the PKK militants to launch cross-border attacks on the
Turkish territory, Cem said.
</P>
<P>
Cem's remarks came after high-ranking officials from both
countries ended a two-day secret security meeting held in
Turkey's southern province of Adana.
</P>
<P>
Both sides held the meeting to ease their mounting tensions
in the past three weeks after Turkey claimed that it would take
decisive measures against the PKK camps in Syria.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz confirmed that
PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan "has been spotted in a Moscow suburb."
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey "has already made all necessary
diplomatic efforts to Russia to ask the extradition of the PKK
leader."
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of harboring the PKK which has
been fighting a 14-year-old separatist war for autonomy in
southeastern Turkey. But Syria has denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Syria has criticized Turkey for forming a military alliance
with Israel, which it said threatens Arab security and undermines
its bargaining positions in negotiations with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has massed heavy forces along the Syrian border and
issued an ultimatum, threatening to uproot PKK bases in Syria by
force if Damascus fails to stop supporting the PKK within 45
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
