<HEADLINE> Czech President Pays Tribute to Ulster Peace Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Czech President Vaclav Havel
Tuesday paid tribute to Northern Ireland's historic peace
agreement, saying reconciliation was the cornerstone.
</P>
<P>
Havel, who is on a four-day visit to Britain, visited Northern
Ireland early Tuesday and met Protestant and Catholic politicians
who negotiated the so-called Good Friday Agreement on April 10.
</P>
<P>
"What is much more important than technical procedural aspects
of arrangements is the underlying idea, the underlying commitment
to peace, to human rights, to human liberties, to mutual respect
between people coming from different traditions -- the idea which
makes up arrangements just agreed here in Northern Ireland," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Havel stressed that reconciliation was its cornerstone and he
wanted through his voice and presence "to add strength to the idea
behind the peace process, to the idea of reconciliation in
Northern Ireland."
</P>
<P>
He also congratulated Northern Ireland's First Minister David
Trimble and Catholic nationalist leader John Hume on being
awarded the Nobel Peace Prize last Friday for their joint efforts
at creating stability in Northern Ireland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
