<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnia, Herzegovina Mired in External Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Bosnia and Herzegovina may have
to raise new loans to clear its old debts, a report released
Tuesday by the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economy indicated.
</P>
<P>
The report said the country does not have the ability to pay
its external debts on time which amount to 3.4 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Minister of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economy
Nikola Grabovoc said enterprises in the country may have to
struggle to the year 2036 to clear all the debts they owe.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement with the country, once enterprises
are in arrears with their debt payments, the government should be
held responsible.
</P>
<P>
Grabovoc said the three-people entities in the country have
agreed that under the above-mentioned circumstance, each entity
should pay its debts respectively.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported that members of the Paris Club of
Creditors have indicated that they may call off the 686 million
dollars in debts that Bosnia and Herzegovina owed before war broke
out in 1991.
</P>
<P>
According to official information from related institutions,
Bosnia and Herzegovina must annually repay 140 to 150 million
dollars of matured debts.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the country recorded a remarkable trade deficit with
an annual export volume of 130 million dollars against a
1-billion-dollar import volume.
</P>
<P>
The war-torn country's economy has been mired in debt in the
recent past with a gross national product of only 15 percent of
what it was in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
