<HEADLINE> U.S. New House Construction Declines in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nationwide new
house construction declined for the second consecutive month in
September, the Commerce Department reported here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Builders started work on homes and apartments at a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 1.58 million last month, down 2.5 percent
from August. Construction starts had hit an 11-year high of 1.70
million in July, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
In another sign that the housing construction market probably
reached a peak in the summer, housing permits plunged 4.5 percent
in September, the largest decline since January 1995.
</P>
<P>
In September, housing starts in the South dropped 8.6 percent,
the largest decline since May 1997, to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 709,000. Analysts believed that the Hurricane
Georges set back builders in Mississippi, Louisiana and other
parts of the South.
</P>
<P>
Starts also fell in the Northeast, down 3.6 percent to a rate
of 135,000. But they rose 5.6 percent in the West to 414,000 and
3.2 percent in the Midwest to 318,000.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, the decline was steeper for apartments, down 9.1
percent to a rate of 330,000, than for single-family homes, down
0.6 percent to 1.25 million.
</P>
<P>
In a separate survey report, the National Association of Home
Builders said traffic of prospective buyers through model homes
fell sharply this month, though sales remained good.
</P>
<P>
Both new and existing homes have been selling strongly this
year, supported by mortgage rates sinking to levels unseen since
the 1960s and by low unemployment and strong income growth. The
remarkable stock market gains through midsummer also gave some
buyers the wherewithal for down payments on larger homes.
</P>
<P>
However, overseas financial chaos has begun to slow U.S.
economic growth, and the stock market, despite a rebound over the
past week, is still well off its mid-July peak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
