<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orthopedic Problems on Rise in Indian Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 21 (Xinhua) -- There is a phenomenal
increase in orthopedic problems in New Delhi, capital of India,
due to increase in life span and "modernization", experts said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With average life expectancy increasing up to 60 years in India
as against 45 years at the time of the country's independence in
1947, two problems facing the metro are breaking bones and
cracking joints, Delhi orthopedists association members told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The disease of "porous bone" osteoporosis is making inroads as
a "silent epidemic" with about 35 percent of post menopausal women
getting affected, they said.
</P>
<P>
In order to take stock of the situation and lay emphasis on
adequate training of professionals to deal with the disease, a
two-day meeting of orthopedists from across the country and abroad
will be convened on October 24 and the meeting will be preceded by
four workshops in different hospitals in the capital, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
