<HEADLINE> Blair Says UK to Back Defense Role for Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair has indicated that his country is prepared for the first
time to give European Union (EU) a defense role in conducting
peacekeeping missions in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Blair said in an interview with Wednesday's The Times newspaper
that Britain was ready to drop Britain's long-standing objections
to the EU having a defense capability.
</P>
<P>
Blair noted that he would put forward some concrete proposals
on promoting EU defense capability at the EU special summit due to
be held in Austria over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
However, Blair made it clear that he was not talking about a
setting up a permanent "European army", which would be put under
direct command of the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing must happen that in any way impinges on the
effectiveness of NATO. NATO for us is the absolutely correct
forum," Blair said, but adding the Kosovo crisis had underlined
the need for Europe to take a very hard-headed view and make sure
that it could fulfill its responsibilities properly.
</P>
<P>
"We should be prepared to think more boldly and more
imaginatively about how we do that. All I am saying is that we
need to allow fresh thinking in this," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
"It is important for Britain to be part of that thinking and
not for us simply to stand there and say we are not part of this,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
