<HEADLINE> Clinton May Return to Mideast Summit Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has not decided Wednesday whether or not to return to the
Palestine-Israel summit talks, which run inton a seventh day in
rural Maryland.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will brief President
Bill Clinton on the Middle East peace talks in rural Maryland, and
could advise him to return to the meeting site, White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
"By early this afternoon, she'll make a judgment on whether
they need to continue working among themselves there today or
whether it would be useful and productive for the president to
return," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Albright, who have been staying in the Wye Plantation,
Maryland, 110 km east from Washington, was expected to brief
Clinton by telephone, he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also discounted media reports of an imminent deal
in the talks between Israeli and Palestinian officials.
</P>
<P>
"I would dissuade you from the sense that there is some deal on
the table," Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has travelled to Wye Plantation, a conference center on
the eastern shore of the Chesapeake Bay, for five of the six
completed days of the peace talks, and could go there again if
Albright thinks it would be productive, Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Reports had said that some progress has been achieved in the
talks and leaders are expected sign an agreement on Thursday at
the White House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
