<HEADLINE> Australian Teenager Sensation Reaches Quarter-finals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Australia's Lleyton Hewitt
made his way up to the singles quarter-finals after beating South
Korea's Lee Hyung-taik in two straight sets at the CMG Asia Hong
Kong Open Challenger tennis tournament here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old made the tennis world sit up and take notice
of him in January, when the wild-card entry upset such stars as
Andre Agassi and Jason Stoltenberg on way to his first victory of
an ATP Tour event in his Australian hometown Adelaide. He became
one of the youngest players in history of Open tennis to win a
title.
</P>
<P>
Hewitt, eighth seed at the nine-day Hong Kong Open, which
opened in the Victoria Park here last Saturday, won over the
South Korean 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Sixth seeded Dutchman Dennis van Scheppingen needed
just 38 minutes to beat Spaniard Oscar Burrieza 6-3, 6-0 to
become the first player into the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
Fifth seed Justin Gimelstob from the United States joined in
when he finished off his rain-interrupted match from the night
before by winning over another South Korean Yoon Yong-Il 6-3,
6-2.
</P>
<P>
Also qualified for the top eight was American Cecil Mamiit who
stopped Japanese Satoshi Iwabuchi 4-6, 6-0, 6-1 on Wednesday.
</P>
