<HEADLINE> Italy's New Government Takes Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME October (Xinhua) -- Italy's 56th government since World
War II took office Wednesday with the swearing in of the new Premier
Massimo D'Alema and a government which includes the
first Communist Cabinet ministers in half a century.
</P>
<P>
President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro officiated over the ceremony in
the Quirinal Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Italy's first ex-communist premier conferred
with the speakers of the Lower House and Senate on putting
confidence votes on the calendar.
</P>
<P>
After a 30-minute talk with Italian Senate Speaker Nicola
Mancino, D'Alema said he intended to ask for the confidence test
in the Lower House.
</P>
<P>
"within the week, I asked Mancino to move as quickly as possible
because the timetable for the budget is pressing," he added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on his new cabinet, he said, "I think a balance has
been found between the requirement of political representation in
a coalition government and personal qualities and skills."
</P>
<P>
D'Alema noted that the government includes a number of people
who are not strongly associated with political parties and that
the number of women has been raised to six. "A correct and
necessary commitment, a signal to the country."
</P>
<P>
He also named Carlo Azeglio Ciampi and Giuliano Amato, at the
treasury and new institutional reform portfolio, as among those
ministers of "prestige, representing the country's various
cultural areas, Socialist, Catholic, and the secular and liberal
world."
</P>
<P>
Speaking of difficulties he encountered in forging a government
based on a coalition which ranges from a small Marxist party to
Catholics in ex-President Francesco Cossiga's ODR, D'Alema said,
"There was no drama, only the problems which normally appear in
these cases." 
</P>
</TEXT>
