<HEADLINE> Rules for Clinton's Impeachment Inquiry Under Discussion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Lawyers from the White House
and the Judiciary Committee of the House of Representatives will
meet Wednesday to discuss how the House impeachment inquiry of
President Bill Clinton will be handled.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart called it a "preliminary
meeting" to find out the "rules of the road" for the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
No major decisions about who will testify and whether the
hearings will be open or closed are expected to come
from the meeting or even before the November 3 elections.
</P>
<P>
The panel's republicans will urge the White House to expedite
the inquiry by agreeing to basic facts in Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr's case against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The republicans also plan to ask White House lawyers for the
exculpatory information they have and will explain their rights
during the inquiry, including their ability to attend all sessions
and to ask witnesses questions.
</P>
<P>
Democrats on the committee argued that Starr should be
subpoenaed to testify and criticized him for not disclosing his
contacts with lawyers for Paula Jones, who has a sexual-harassment
suit against Clinton, before he began investigating the Monica
Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
Democrats also insist that before any basic facts are agreed
upon, Republicans should first decide whether Starr's charges --
if true -- are grounds for impeachment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
