<HEADLINE> Four-party Talks Resume in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The four-party talks on the
Korean Peninsula issue resumed here on Wednesday after a six-month
break.
</P>
<P>
The talks, aimed at initiating a new mechanism for peace
instead of an armistice in the Korean Peninsula, were attended by
representatives from the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea(DPRK), South Korea, China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Qian Yongnian, who is also the Chinese delegation
leader, said in his opening statement that the talks have entered
a key phase. He urged all parties to face reality and make joint
efforts to push the talks forward in a frank, sincere, pragmatic
and flexible manner.
</P>
<P>
There still exists tension and confrontation in the Korean
Peninsula, which is a result of the cold war in the Peninsula and
mutual distrust among all sides, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
He called on all sides to proceed from a sense of urgency and
responsibility to promote the talks, while cherishing the fruits
that have already been secured.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation will keep in close contact through
consultations and cooperation with all sides and do its best to
help create a peace mechanism in the Korean Peninsula as quickly
as possible, Qian added.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Charles Kartman from the United States, South Korean
deputy Foreign Minister Kim Kye-Gwa, and the DPRK's Ambassador
Park Kun-Woo also expressed their views at the opening
ceremony. They all stressed the willingness to strengthen
cooperation and overcome difficulties. They also pledged to make
active efforts to make progress in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Swiss Secretary of Foreign Affairs Jakob Kellenberger, on
behalf of the host, also delivered a speech.
</P>
<P>
The talks, scheduled to end on October 25, are chaired by South
Korea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
