<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Rejects Pakistan's Precondition for No-War Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 21 (Xinhua) -- An External Affairs Ministry
spokesman said Wednesday that India has rejected Pakistan's
precondition of seeking a successful resolution of the Jammu and
Kashmir issue for negotiating a no-war pact.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's offer was formally made to India during the foreign
secretary-level talks in Islamabad last week with the rider that
such a pact could be negotiated only after successful resolution
of the Jammu and Kashmir issue, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Re-introduction of the caveat is not acceptable to us as it
negates the very concept of a non-aggression pact," he said adding
that India could not accept any such linkages.
</P>
<P>
During the foreign secretary-level talks last week, both India
and Pakistan had put forward their proposals on confidence
building measures.
</P>
<P>
India's proposals included agreement to prevent nuclear
conflict through accidental or unauthorized use of nuclear
weapons, assurance that flight tests would not be in each other's
direction, cessation of firing incidents on Line of Control and
asking Pakistan to forthwith stop aiding and abetting terrorist
activities in India.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's proposals included setting up a nuclear risk
reduction center, bilateral agreement on banning nuclear tests,
acceptance of a minimum nuclear deterrent, prevention of violation
of air space and territorial waters and revival of pre-Simla
agreement border ground rules, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to be Successful in Economy: U.S. Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 21 (Xinhua) -- United States ambassador
to Tanzania Rev. Charles Stith said here Wednesday that Tanzania
is set to become an economically prosperous country.
</P>
<P>
"Tanzania is poised to be Africa's successful economic story,"
said Stith, in the first press conference he held in Tanzania
since he came to office last month.
</P>
<P>
Stith cited three reasons which will lead to the success of
Tanzania, one of the poorest country in the world.
</P>
<P>
First, he said, Tanzania enjoys high level of stability as
opposed to neighboring countries like Burundi, Rwanda and the
Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Even some east European countries cannot compare to Tanzania
in this regard, the U.S. diplomat said at his residence.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, Tanzania has viable democracy, he said, noting that
the country has completed peaceful transition of power after free
elections with a good political climate like free press.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, Tanzania is a big country with rich natural resources
where foreign companies are willing to invest, Stith said, adding
that he was encouraged by the spirit of mining developers in
several areas he toured.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania can become an economy like South Africa in the
continent, said the U.S. envoy.
</P>
<P>
However, Stith suggested that Tanzania should try to eliminate
corruption, saying "any corruption is much corruption."
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said the United States will develop relations
with African countries based on trade other than simply on aid
which might be a burden.
</P>
<P>
On the investigation of the bombing at the U.S. embassy on
August 7, Stith said that it is proceeding as more evidence is
collected day by day.
</P>
<P>
"We'll not rest. We'll not relent until those responsible for
committing the crimes are brought to justice," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The bomb attack on the U.S. embassy in Dar es Salaam killed 11
people and injured more than 70 others. Two suspects, an
Egyptian national and a Tanzanian has been charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Dudley O. Sims, the director of the United States
Information Service (USIS) in Tanzania, told Xinhua at a
refreshment after the press conference that the blast was not
caused by a bomb buried in a water tanker as previously believed,
because the body of its driver was found at the scene.
</P>
<P>
Had the powerful bomb been buried in the water tanker, the
body of the driver could have been blasted into pieces with few
traces, he further explained.
</P>
<P>
He said FBI believes that two vehicles have been used by
bombing suspects, one was a refrigeration truck, the other is a
smaller Suzuki Samurai used for transporting explosives.
</P>
<P>
The truck may follow the water tanker when the blast occurred,
he said, adding that the vehicle may have burst into pieces at
the scene.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian police and FBI are still tracking the smaller
vehicle which remains at large, said Sims.
</P>
<P>
He also said the accurate time of the bombing was 10:39 a.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
