<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joint Venture to Improve Power Supply in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique, South Africa and
Swaziland set up a joint venture MOTRACO recently, which is set
to improve the power supply in south Mozambique and Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
According to Wednesday's Noticias, with a capital of 40
million U.S. Dollars, MOTRACO will mainly provide electricity to
MOZAL, a Mozambican aluminum company, apart from meeting the
needs of power for southern Mozambique and Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's EDM and South Africa's ESKOM hold one third of
the shares in the venture respectively while the rest goes to
Swazi and other share-holders.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Mozambican and South African firms signed
the agreement on the establishment of the joint venture.
</P>
<P>
Juliao Pondeca who is in charge of MOTRACO, said a 900-km
transmission line worth 130 million U.S. Dollars will be put up
between South Africa and the Beloluane Power Substation near
Maputo, capital of Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the power will come from Cahora Bassa
Station in northwest Mozambique. Once the price of electricity
is settled, power will go to South Africa, and again via the
transmission line in South Africa to Maputo if Mozambique in turn
agrees to buy the electricity from South Africa's ESKOM.
</P>
<P>
Swaziland will benefit from the line because part of it will
pass through the kingdom. For this a transformer will be built in
Swaziland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
