<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fifth HLHL Prizes to Be Awarded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Ho Leung Ho Lee (HLHL)
Foundation has decided to cancel a scheduled ceremony marking its
fifth anniversary because of the summer floods.
</P>
<P>
The HLHL Foundation will present awards to this year's prize
winners tomorrow at the Great Hall of the People in Beijing, said
Duan Ruichun, member and secretary general of the Foundation's
Selection Board.
</P>
<P>
The HLHL Foundation was registered in Hong Kong in March of
1994 with 400 million HK dollars donated by Dr. S.H. Ho,
Dr. Kau-Kui Leung, Dr. Ho Tim and Dr. Quo-Wei Lee.
</P>
<P>
The Foundation is considered the largest support group for
science and technology from both at home and abroad. It bestows
two awards, one for science and technology achievement, and the
other for progress in science and technology. Winners of the first
award will receive one million HK dollars each.
</P>
<P>
The former award is granted to those who have worked for the
promotion of science and technology in China for a long time, made
significant contributions, and scored world-class achievements in
their academic fields. The latter award is granted to those who
have made important inventions or made discoveries in specific
areas, especially in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Foundation, following the Nobel Prize selection process,
consists of some 1,400 domestic and overseas experts. Two teams of
eminent scientists make first and final selections of the winners
through secret ballots.
</P>
<P>
The HLHL Foundation has granted 13 outstanding scientists with
achievement awards, and 173 excellent scientists with progress
awards since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Quo-Wei Lee expressed his intention of supporting Chinese
scientists with a special foundation at a meeting with
Vice-Premier Zhu Rongji in June 1993.
</P>
<P>
This intention was turned into reality after 10-months of joint
efforts of various sectors in Beijing and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It was a sad occasion when the list of the first group of award
winners was faxed from Beijing to Hong Kong to Dr. Kau-Kui Leung,
a founder of the foundation, who had passed away on November 10,
1994 at the age of 91.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Rongji highly praised the HLHL Foundation and the four
founders and their relatives, saying their "noteworthy and noble
conduct will not only benefit the present, but also find favor far
into the future."
</P>
<P>
Donators and their relatives expressed the hope that the HLHL
Foundation will play a more significant role in advancing
scientific research and training professionals and that, in turn,
Hong Kong will benefit from its scientific and technological
advancement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
