<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assault Accusers Seek Settlement with Tyson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Mike Tyson got his boxing
license back and now he's trying to avoid another court date.
</P>
<P>
Two men who have accused Tyson of assaulting them after a
minor traffic accident on August 31 in Montgomery County,
Maryland, near Washington D.C., are negotiating a financial
settlement, according to their attorneys.
</P>
<P>
They also want Tyson to get psychiatric help, not punishment.
The former heavyweight champion's defense attorney, Paul F.
Kemp,has said he has asked Montgomery County prosecutors to have
Tyson's second-degree assault charges dismissed if the alleged
victims agree to a "compromise."
</P>
<P>
"We are at the stage where we believe we will be able to
resolve our civil claims," said Glenn Culpepper, a lawyer for one
of the men, Abmielec Saucedo.
</P>
<P>
Tyson's probation status for an Indiana rape could be affected
by conviction in the Maryland assault cases.
</P>
<P>
"They didn't have as an objective to punish him or put him in
jail or strip him off his livelihood," said Roger W. Titus, an
attorney for the second man, Richard Hardick.
</P>
<P>
Titus said both men had filed criminal complaints against
Tyson to achieve three goals: for Tyson to apologize, for the
boxer to get help for whatever made him allegedly attack them
after the accident and for him to compensate them financially.
</P>
<P>
Tyson, who has pleaded not guilty, is set to go on trial for
the two misdemeanor assault charges on December 1. If convicted,
he faces a maximum 10 years in prison on each charge.
</P>
<P>
During a hearing before the Nevada State Athletic Commission,
which voted Monday to return his boxing license, Tyson said he
"didn't really hit anybody".
</P>
<P>
Neither Titus nor Culpepper would comment on the size of the
financial agreement being negotiated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
