<HEADLINE> Compensation Paid for Vessels Used to Plug Dike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The city government of
Jiujiang in east China's Jiangxi Province paid 3.07 million yuan
Wednesday to compensate for vessels used to plug a burst dike
of the Yangtze River during the summer floods.
</P>
<P>
A section of the city's defence embankments collapsed on August
7, and in the following days local authorities held up 10 vessels
of various kinds to fill up the gap in the line, in accordance
with anti-flood law.
</P>
<P>
On September 22, the city government has sent an expert team to
assess the losses to the ship-owners, and it was finally decided
to pay for eight of them, as the owners of the other two had
volunteered to donate their boats.
</P>
<P>
The compensation also covers four other vessels that were
partly damaged while being used to transport materials to plug
the burst.
</P>
<P>
The Jiujiang burst was one of the most serious incidents during
the two-month nationwide efforts to combat the severe floods, the
worst since 1954. The floods claimed 3,004 lives and affected more
than 230 million people.
</P>
<P>
According to previous reports, no casualties were caused by the
Jiujiang incident, but at least 40,000 soldiers were involved in
the plugging and other activities to save this industrial and
tourist city. The cause of the burst is still under
investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
