<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The U.N. World Food Program has said it will ensure an
annual supply of 37,000 tonnes of foodstuffs to Yemen during
1998-2001.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily Al Hayat said that Yemen is classified as one
of the least developed and food-deficient countries, with about
20 percent of its population living under the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Minister of Agriculture and Water Abdullah Bin
Abdul-Aziz Bin Moammar said efforts will be made to increase
industrial investments in foodstuff industry, particularly that of
palm dates.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Wednesday that Saudi date
production reaches 600,000 tonnes a year with palm trees of about
18 million.
</P>
<P>
Moammar said the number of plants engaged in date processing
has risen to 36 and 60 percent of the production is exported to
Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The footware branch of the Chamber of Commerce in
Cairo has called for an increase of tariffs on imported shoes and
leather products to protect domestic production.
</P>
<P>
In a report submitted to the government, the branch said it was
the first step to counter unfair competition posed by imported
shoes.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian trade representative office in Jakarta said
that Egypt's imports from Indonesia rose by 22.2 percent in the
first five months this year, compared with the corresponding
period last year to reach 98.4 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Most of the imports are raw materials and semi-finished goods
needed in domestic industries, such as timber, paper, yarn,
textiles, tea, glass and some chemicals.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has been listed for the first time by the
British weekly "The Economist" as one of the rising markets,
Egyptian Arabic daily Alam Al Yom reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the only Arab state incorporated in the list, which
includes 25 markets.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is the second in Africa to be incorporated in the rank
after South Africa and the third in the Middle East together with
Israel and Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
