<HEADLINE> Saleh Praises Yemeni-U.S. Military Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni President Ali Abdullah
Saleh expressed his appreciation of the Yemeni-U.S. cooperation in
the military and other fields.
</P>
<P>
Saleh made the comment during a meeting here Wednesday with
Admiral Charles William Moore, commander of the Middle East
central naval force and commander of the U.S. Fifth Fleet.
</P>
<P>
According to the Yemeni News Agency, their meeting dealt with
bilateral relations and areas of cooperation, foremost among which
was their military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Saleh praised the military cooperation in training, exchange of
expertise and mine sweeping, saying it symbolized the overall
friendship and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He further expressed Yemen's interest in promoting relations
with U.S. to "meet the expectations of the two peoples and ensure
common interests."
</P>
<P>
Moore congratulated Saleh and Yemeni people for the favorable
international arbitration which enabled Yemen to reclaim
sovereignty over most of the southern Red Sea Hanish islands, at
the center of a dispute with Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Yemen clashed with Eritrea, the neighbor across the Red Sea,
over the Hanish Archipelago in 1995, but the two countries agreed
in 1996 to resort the dispute to international arbitration.
</P>
<P>
He described the outcome of the arbitration as a good example
to be followed in resolving border disputes among states.
</P>
<P>
Moore, who arrived in Sanaa Monday on a visit, praised the
steady development of Yemeni-U.S. relations in the military and
other fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
