<HEADLINE> S'pore Chosen as Caltex Global Corporate Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 21 (Xinhua)-- Singapore has expressed its
welcome to an announcement Wednesday by a U.S. oil company that
the city state has been selected to relocate its global corporate
headquarters, the first of its kind in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Caltex Petroleum Corporation, a U.S.-based corporation that has
7,700 people and 13 refineries as well as 8,500 retail service
stations in more than 60 countries and areas in Asia, Africa and
the Middle East, affirmed that its corporate executive leadership
would be relocated to Singapore during the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Philip Yeo, chairman of the Economic Development Board (EDB) of
Singapore, said, "Caltex will be the first multinational company
to establish its global corporate headquarters in Singapore" and
"EDB warmly welcomes Caltex to make Singapore its home."
</P>
<P>
The corporation, which is now based in Dallas, and will remain
registered in the U.S., said in a press release that the decision
to relocate came after reorganization of the company's worldwide
operations and extensive research into an optimal location for its
executive staff.
</P>
<P>
In June, Caltex extensively reorganized its operations to focus
primarily on specific lines of business rather than focus on a
geographic structure in response to a growing worldwide
deregulation of the markets for petroleum products, and enable the
company to improve operating efficiencies, focus its expertise,
and facilitate the sharing of knowledge across markets.
</P>
<P>
Caltex business units for trading, marketing, lubricants and
new business development will also be based in Singapore and its
new location will become operational by March 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
