<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development Priority in Human Rights Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Experts attending the
International Symposium on World Human Rights Towards the 21st
Century pointed out here today that the development of human
rights should conform to social progress.
</P>
<P>
Wang Shunzhu, a researcher with the Beijing Society for
Comparative International Studies, said human rights is not
an isolated issue, but reflects every area of people's
material and spiritual lives, so "the progress of human rights
should be compatible with the level of social productive forces
and production relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the end of World War II in 1945, emphasis on human rights
has shifted to self-determination, development, peace, natural
sources, the environment, and humanitarian assistance.
</P>
<P>
The United States adopted the Universal Declaration of Human
Rights in 1948 and the International Covenant on Civil and Political
Rights 18 years later, which have served as major documents on human
rights.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Gerasimovich, Vice Foreign Minister of Belarus, called
the right of development the basis of human rights in accordance
with the current situation and prospect of human rights.
</P>
<P>
Only
when the development right is actually realized in the fields of
politics, economy, society and culture, can people live a wealthy,
healthy and hopeful life, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Zhong Shukong, member of the UN Sub-Commission on Prevention of
Discrimination and Protection of Minorities, pointed out that it
is urgent to promote the realization of the right of development,
and that economic and social development compatible with national
situations is crucial to social stability and progress.
</P>
<P>
He urged that both developing and developed countries
contribute to global sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
Hector Cuadra-Moreno, professor at the National University of
Mexico, said that what people need now is preferential
economic policies to improve their living conditions, the creation of more
jobs, and increasing investment in housing, hospitals, schools,
public traffic and social security.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhuqian, an official of the Commission of Legislative
Affairs of the National People's Congress Standing Committee,
stressed that promoting general development that centers on
a booming economy will eventually lead to human-rights progress.
</P>
<P>
China now is making great efforts to feed and clothe its
people in poverty-stricken areas with the aim of generally
improving people's lives, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N., Taliban to Sign Security Agreement Friday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations and
Afghanistan's Taliban are set to sign an agreement on security
arrangements for the U.N. personnel in Afghanistan, a senior
Taliban official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides are stateside with the three-day talks, which will
also continue tomorrow (Thursday)," Taliban's representative
Saeed-ur-Rehman Haqqani told Xinhua here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"I am hopeful that the two sides will ink the accord on
Friday," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that the current talks would pave way for the
resumption of relief activities by the U.N. and international
non-governmental organizations in the war-torn Afghanistan," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have agreed on seven points of the 14-point
agenda and the rest would be discussed in the next round of
meeting, the Taliban official said.
</P>
<P>
During Monday's talks, the U.N. offered the security
sub-agreement which calls for official protection for the world
body's premises and also promises of its implementing partners and
mobile mission.
</P>
<P>
The said agreement also asks guarantee that if any U.N. staff
member is detained they should be released in 72 hours in absence
of formal charges against them, and the U.N. staff would be
allowed if they want to visit any of its detained staff.
</P>
<P>
Taliban's paramount leader Mulla Muhammad Omar in his last
week's meeting with U.N. special envoy Lakhdar Brahimi in
Kandahar, southern Afghanistan, urged the world body and other aid
groups to resume their humanitarian operations in the war-ravaged
country.
</P>
<P>
International aid agencies suspended their operations in
Taliban-controlled areas over a row on the relocation of their
offices by the Islamic movement in an old building on the
outskirts of Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. withdrew its expatriate staff from Afghanistan in
August following the killing of an Italian national working for
the U.N. in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi, whose shuttle diplomacy helped avert a possible war
between Iran and Taliban, also expressed the hope Monday that the
U.N. and other aid groups would return to Afghanistan following
security guarantees from the militia authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
