<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Eximbank Supports Foreign Trade Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- By the end of August, China's
Export and Import Bank (Eximbank) had ratified 616 supplier's
credit programs and six buyer's credit programs to support
exports of electronics and machinery products with a contracted
value of 17.25 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered at the Fourth Annual Meeting of Asian
Export Credit Agencies held today in Beijing, Vice-Governor of
Eximbank Gu Mingchao said that Eximbank has played a significant
role in China's foreign trade development and the country's
macroeconomic restructuring since its founding four years ago.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, he said, the business volume of the
bank's export supplier's credit increased 13 times over that of
1994.
</P>
<P>
Gu said the bank has also expanded its export credit varieties
in recent years, which presently include project credit, medium-
and short-term quota credit, overseas engineering contract credit,
overseas facilities credit and overseas investment credit for
electronic and machinery products.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Eximbank's export credit insurance and
foreign-oriented warranty business have also experienced rapid
development, with a sharp increase in volume.
</P>
<P>
He said this year the bank will further expand its client
base to include both state-owned large enterprises and
collectively owned enterprises, as well as shareholding
enterprises and small businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Dialog Represents Trend for International Exchanges on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The two-day international
symposium on world human rights, the first event of its kind held
in China, closed today in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The symposium provided a excellent opportunity for officials
and scholars from China and 26 nations to have a free exchange of
views on human rights and proved that dialog is the only choice
for promoting the cause of international human rights.
</P>
<P>
In February this year, the European Union (EU) announced that it
would not table proposals against China during the United Nations
Conference on Human Rights, and that it would engage in
constructive dialog with China rather than spark confrontation
concerning human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
The EU decision isolated the United States which itself issued
a March announcement that it would not propose any motion against
China during the conference. The decision effectively ended the
farce of a small number of countries proposing motions against
China during successive conference since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the leaders of Western nations, including France,
Germany and Italy, have voiced hope for settling their disputes
with China concerning human rights through dialog carried out on
the basis of mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
Increasing calls for "dialog" in the international human right
arena fully demonstrates that trend for dialog to replace
confrontation has greatly enhance the worldwide human rights. At
the same time, attempts to use human rights as a weapon to
interfere in the internal affairs of other countries has had
little effect.
</P>
<P>
Human rights, a lofty goal of the mankind, should be valued by
every nation. However, at least for a certain period of time,
developed nations used human rights issues as a pretext for
attacking developing nations.
</P>
<P>
For example, the human right report issued early this year by
the U.S. State Department claimed that China has forced residents
to move from poverty-stricken mountain areas and has undermined
the traditional way of life of related ethnic groups. In fact,
resettling residents from adverse circumstances is part of the
Chinese government's effort to help them escape poverty and has
been warmly welcome by those involved.
</P>
<P>
The report which wantonly criticized human right situations in
194 countries and regions has been rejected by many countries in
Asia, Africa, Latin America and Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Dialogue Represents Trend for International Exchanges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although the criteria for human rights is at least in principle
of universal significance, the focus and way each nation realizes
related goals vary due to significant differences in history,
culture, social systems and economic development.
</P>
<P>
A nation's choice of avenues for reaching goals represents a
basic human right in itself. However, the practise of commenting
on the situations in other countries on a biased basis, or
threatening to impose various sanctions under the pretext of human
rights, constitute violations of the basic precept.
</P>
<P>
Such practices neither promote the development of the
international human right cause, nor improve relations between
developed and developing countries.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, only the government and people of a nation
are qualified to comment on human right conditions in their own
countries. The responsibility for protecting and promoting human
rights and fundamental freedom lies in the governments of
individual nations, according to comments Mary Robinson, high
commissioner of the UN Human Right Affair Office, made to the UN
Human Right Commission.
</P>
<P>
For example, the top priority of the Chinese government is to
provide its 1.2 billion people with adequate food and
clothing. Any other approach would represent a gross exaggeration
of human rights.
</P>
<P>
China has not only enjoyed political stability and rapid
economic growth, but has witnessed monumental improvements in
human rights over the past 20 years solely because it economic and
social policies suited to national conditions.
</P>
<P>
China has affixed its signature to 17 international human
rights documents, including the International Covenant for Civil
Rights and Political Rights signed earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the current international situation, peace and
development far outweigh the Cold War and are indeed the trend of
the times. Now is the time for certain politicians and
organizations in the United States and a few other countries to
change their thinking and do some practical things for the
promotion of international human rights.
</P>
<P>
Human rights situation in any country is far from perfect and
the promotion and protection of human rights represents a gradual
long-term. It is quite obvious that the choice of dialog instead
of confrontation will better serve the progress of the human right
cause worldwide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
