<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mahathir: Malaysia Not to Bow to West Demands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Wednesday that the West wants Asian
countries to open up everything, but Malaysia is not prepared to
bow to their demands.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the West had constantly branded Asian countries
as crony capitalists when their governments closed their doors to
foreign participation.
</P>
<P>
"What the West wants from Asian countries is to open up
everything to foreigners on grounds that their (Western) companies
are the most efficient ones. They suggested that if we don't open
up to them, it is crony capitalism," Mahathir told a news
conference here Wednesday evening on his just-concluded five-day
working visit to Japan.
</P>
<P>
He said that in most Asian countries, restrictions had been
imposed on foreign participation, particularly from the West.
</P>
<P>
In Malaysia's case, Mahathir said, the government preferred to
provide opportunities to its own people through privatization, a
move which was not favored by the West.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We don't want our companies to be taken over, that is
why we did not accept the International Monetary Fund (IMF) aid
because one of the Fund's conditions is to open up the economy by
100 percent."
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is not prepared to bow to their demands, Mahathir
said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said he believed the West would push its cause through
the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Japan itself did not want to see Americans taking
over companies and in fact, Japan's restrictions are more tighter
than Malaysia's.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysia's views on managing its economy were
gaining acceptance. Even U.S. billionaire financier and currency
speculator George Soros himself had accepted Malaysia's stand on
limits to financial speculation and was supportive of measures
introduced by Malaysia, he added.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said many parties, who had earlier blamed Asian
governments for the regional crisis, were now condemning currency
traders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
