<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea's Former Kia Boss Sentenced to Seven Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The former boss of South Korean
Kia Group, Kim Sun-hong, was sentenced to seven years in prison
Wednesday for embezzling company funds and guaranteeing debts for
insolvent subsidiaries, which led to the group's bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
Kim, who headed Kia until last October, was convicted of
illegally ordering the group's flagship, Kia Motors, to lend 1.1
trillion won (some 1.1 billion U.S. dollars at the time) to four
troubled subsidiaries and guarantee 2.8 trillion won (2.8 billion
dollars) in debts incurred by them.
</P>
<P>
Along with Kim, four former Kia executives were given prison
terms ranging from 3 years to 3.5 years for their involvement in
the scandal.
</P>
<P>
Kim, once called South Korea's "Lee Iacocca" since he made Kia
Motors the nation's second largest auto company, was also found
guilty of diverting some 52.3 billion won (52.3 million dollars)
of company funds to a dubious in-house committee in an attempt to
keep control of Kia.
</P>
<P>
Kim and the other four were also found guilty of creating
enormous financial burdens for the group, deceiving shareholders
and weakening financial institutes.
</P>
<P>
Kia went bankrupt with 11.7 trillion won (11.7 billion dollars)
of debts in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The conviction came two days after Kia Motors and its sister
company Asia Motors were sold at auction to Hyundai Motor Co.,
South Korea's top carmaker.
</P>
<P>
Kia's collapse, coupled with the failure of other large groups
in South Korea and Asia's financial crisis, brought the country
into a foreign exchange crisis and forced Seoul in December to ask
for a bailout loan of 57 billion dollars from the International
Monetary Fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
