<HEADLINE> HK Revises Visa-free Arrangements for Foreign Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Immigration
Department announced Wednesday the revised visa-free arrangements
for visitors from some countries to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
With effect from October 28 this year, the department said the
visa-free period for visitors from Finland, Germany, Greece, Japan
and the United States will extend from one month to three months;
that for visitors from Sri Lanka and Lesotho will be changed from
original three months to one month and 14 days respectively.
</P>
<P>
Those from Sierra Leone, Nigeria, Nepal and Angola to Hong Kong
need to apply for entry visas beginning from October 28 instead
of previous visa-free arrangements.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Immigration Department said: "It is our
practice to review visa requirements for foreign visitors from
time to time."
</P>
<P>
"Changes are made where necessary to take into account factors
such as our ties with individual countries and track record of
travelers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Hong Kong will continue to adopt a liberal
visa policy on the entry of foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
At present, people from about 170 countries and regions may
visit Hong Kong without visas and stay for from 7 days to six
months. Only people from about 40 countries need to apply for
visas to visit Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
