<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Higher on Asian Stocks Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
closed higher Wednesday as strong Asian markets underpinned gains
in local stocks.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index closed 26.1 points higher at
2,543.0, receiving an early kick along from a stronger Wall Street
overnight and powerful regional markets supported that move later
in the local session.
</P>
<P>
Lucinda Chan from Macquarie Equities said the market closed at
its highest point for the day with some short covering in
afternoon trade.
</P>
<P>
"It's been pretty lackluster," said Chan, adding that there had
been little to drive the market Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Rather, it had been underpinned by solid fundamentals such as
the stable domestic currency, she said.
</P>
<P>
On Australian equities markets, the all resources index firmed
8.6 points to 1,038.2, while the all industrials index jumped 47.4
points to 4,420.2.
</P>
<P>
Chan said News Corp. was one of the notable strong stocks
Wednesday, rising after the media group's Fox Entertainment Group
Inc. in the United States projected a price range of 21 to 24 U.S.
dollars for shares in its planned initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
News Corp.'s shares gained 73.9 cents, while its preferred
scrip added 74.3 cents.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector was also strong, gaining 33.8 points to
close at 5,368.9. National Australia Bank added 1.7 cents, Westpac
rose 25 cents, ANZ gained eight cents while the Commonwealth Bank
bucked the trend to drop 22 cents.
</P>
<P>
In the resource sector, BHP added 24 cents, Rio Tinto added
three, WMC gained 4.4 cents and MIM dropped one cent.
</P>
<P>
The gold index improved 3.7 points to 1,140.0, the price of
gold bullion in Sydney closed at 297.10 U.S. dollars an ounce,
compared to Tuesday's close of 296.25.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 361.98 million stocks traded for 1.006
billion Australian dollars (626.73 million U.S. dollars), with
rising stocks outnumbering falling stocks 500 to 466, while 375
stocks remained steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
