<HEADLINE> Hyundai to Revive 2 Bankrupt Automakers with Big Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Hyundai Motor, the largest
automaker in South Korea, will have to inject 7.6 trillion won
(about 5.8 billion U.S. dollars) in two ailing automakers for
their revival, South Korean creditor banks said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bankrupt Kia Motors Co. and Asia Motors Co. were taken over
by Hyundai at an auction on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Creditor banks said Hyundai will have to buy 153 million shares of
Kia and 61.2 million shares of Asia in accordance with the bidding
terms under which Hyundai must keep 51 percent shares of the
two firms.
</P>
<P>
The Hyundai Motor said it plans to seek capital injection from
foreign automakers and investors in a consortium to share the
financial burden.
</P>
<P>
Although Kia and Asia have owed an estimated 12.8 trillion won
(about 9.7 billion dollars) to financial institutions, Hyundai
will still shoulder a relatively small burden for the time being
as it has a seven-year period to repay the debt, analysts here
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
