<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Closes Steady in Quiet Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
steady Wednesday in quiet trading, as the market kept an eye on
the fortunes of the Japanese yen against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"At the moment it's really stuck in a range, tracking the yen,"
said Clifford Bennett, senior strategist at BNP.
</P>
<P>
The local currency could likely fall below 60.00 U.S. cents,
Bennett said, predicting a recovery in the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"I think the U.S. dollar has bottomed, and so given that we
have a bullish U.S. dollar view, the Aussie is sitting here for
the moment looking to roll over at any time."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended local trade unchanged at 63.20 U.S.
cents, after spending the day between 62.81 and 63.53 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Bennett said there was little justification for a strong
Australian dollar considering the current financial turmoil
affecting the commodity-based currency's key markets.
</P>
<P>
"It shouldn't be up here in the first place," he said. "We are
starting to lose our price competitiveness that was offsetting the
decline in commodities for the last two years."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar finished at 73.41 Japanese yen from 72.84
Tuesday and 1.0341 German marks from 1.0329. 
</P>
</TEXT>
