<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Moves to Trim Non-Plan Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 21 (Xinhua) -- India's Finance Ministry has
begun a weekly monitoring of government expenditure to effect a 10
percent cut in non-plan expenditure as proposed in this year's
budget, official sources said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The government is also monitoring expenditure in projects to
check time and cost overruns and any project above 1,000 million
rupees (23.72 million U.S. dollars) investment is being directly
monitored by the Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
The maximum leakages in expenditure is feared in the social
sector for which annual allocation is around 300 billion rupees
(7.12 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Expenditure Department has already decided to scrutinize
some of the social sector projects to find out if the money was
being spent properly, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The monitoring was being done by Finance Minister Yashwant
Sinha himself, and the comptrollers general of civil accounts in
all ministries have been authorized to carry out this task on a
weekly basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
