<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Rivers in Malaysia Become Polluted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 21 (Xinhua) -- More rivers in Malaysia
became polluted with the number of polluted rivers almost doubled
in 1997 compared to 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to the annual Environmental Quality Report 1997
released here Wednesday, there were 25 polluted rivers last year
compared to 13 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The report prepared by the Department of Environment showed
that the number of clean rivers had decreased from 42 in 1996 to
24 in 1997, while rivers slightly polluted had increased from 61
in 1996 to 68 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The report indicated that sources of river pollution were from
agrobased industries, livestock farms, sewage and manufacturing
activities.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Environment also conducted ground water
quality monitoring and preliminary findings based on samples
analyzed did not show any significant contaminant in ground water.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the 8.5 million registered vehicles in Malaysia
unleashed 1.9 million tons of carbon monoxide into the atmosphere
last year, making it a major source of air pollution in urban
centers, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Apart from carbon monoxide, the vehicles also accounted for
emissions of 224,000 tons of nitrogen oxides, 101,000 tons of
hydrocarbons, 36,000 tons of sulphur dioxide and 16,000 tons of
particulate matter into the atmosphere, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report said public participation in the review of the
Environmental Impact Assessment was still very much lacking
despite growing concern about the environment.
</P>
<P>
The government has been urged to continue with its
environmental education and awareness activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
