<HEADLINE> International Audio &AMP; Visual Show Opens in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The broadcasting industry has
to expand their horizon and enhance technology to cater to the
increasing deed for more information, Director of Broadcasting
Cheung Man Yee of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the international Audio &AMP;
Visual Show '98, Cheung said the exhibition has been instrumental
in promoting Hong Kong SAR's broadcasting industry and high
technology products.
</P>
<P>
Radio Television Hong Kong displayed their Digital Audio
Broadcasting, which is the latest technology in broadcasting.
Presented live to the public for the first time in Hong Kong SAR,
this technology can provide superior sound quality.
</P>
<P>
Jointly organized by the Hong Kong Trade Development Council
and Radio Association of Hong Kong, the five-day event, which was
held here for the 10th year this year, has attracted 50 exhibitors
who had brought with them high-tech models from around the world
including many internationally renowned brands.
</P>
<P>
The AV Show is an effective marketing platform for the
audio-visual industry, said Richard Lee, Chairman of Radio
Association of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"The rapid advancement of technology has brought many exciting
and innovative products to the market. Technological breakthroughs
in AV products, such as the Digital Versatile Disc (DVD) systems
and high-resolution digital television, provide further stimulus
to the market," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's AV equipment industry has to respond quickly to
monitor the changing market trends, and to ensure that effective
marketing services are provided to customers. They also need to
strengthen their quality assurance system to meet the challenge.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong exported more than 112 billion HK dollars (14.3
billion U.S. dollars) worth of these products, major markets
include China's mainland, the United States and the European
Union. Hong Kong imported 142 billion HK dollars (18.2 billion
U.S. dollars) such products last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
