<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Petrol Fire Victims Flee Hospital in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Most of the victims of
Saturday's pipeline fire in southern Nigeria have fled hospitals
for fear of being arrested and charged for their role in the
disaster that have been described by government as act of
sabotage.
</P>
<P>
Disclosing this to newsmen in his office at the
government-owned Central Hospital in Sapele town, where most of
the victims were hospitalized, doctor Hostings Eduvie said there
was a rumor circulating in the area that government plans to
arrest and charge those hospitalized for sabotage, media reports
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Eduvie, who is the medical director of the
hospital, said most of them have voluntarily discharged
themselves.
</P>
<P>
The doctor debunked the claim in some quarters that victims
were forced to leave the hospital because there were no equipment
and drugs to treat them.
</P>
<P>
According to him, oil companies such as Chevron, Shell and
other organizations have sent drugs needed by fire victims.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions at the fire site in Jesse town, near Warri
City, the chairman of the Red Cross Society, Warri Division,
Tenison Unavwobo said his team had recovered over 200 corpses
from River Ethiope and surrounding bushes between Monday and
Tuesday. He said the searchinG would continue.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation (NNPC)
has been ordered to start investigations into the accident, which
the company said was caused by saboteurs who cut the pipeline to
steal petrol\ according to Nigerian leader, General Abdulsalam
Abubakar, who was addressing state house reporters Tuesday in
Abuja.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking to reporters Tuesday at Jesse, NNPC's Executive
Director J.T. Ogungbemi said that more fire fighters would be
brought to the site to distinguish the petrol fire that is still
burning on.
</P>
<P>
More than 700 people were burnt to death at the weekend in a
ferocious fire from burst oil pipeline in Jesse town near Warri
City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
