<HEADLINE> Transport Links to Mainland Vital to HK: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Special
Administrative Region (SAR) official said Wednesday that
linkage with the mainland is a key element in drawing up Hong
Kong's long-term transport blueprint.
</P>
<P>
"One key element in our long-term strategic transport planning
is to look beyond the boundary of Hong Kong," said Anson Chan, the
 SAR's Administrative Secretary, in a keynote speech at the
Asia-Pacific Public Transport congress that opened here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the SAR government has decided to build
a spur line leading to a second rail passenger boundary crossing
in order to meet projected increase in the cross boundary flow of
people and goods.
</P>
<P>
As Hong Kong's economy is becoming increasingly integrated
with the mainland, the daily number of cross boundary vehicles now
has reached 28,000 and is still growing at a rate of six percent
every year. Some 200,000 people cross the border every day,
accounting for three percent of Hong Kong's total population.
</P>
<P>
Chan said that the SAR government is discussing with the
relevant mainland authorities the possibility of opening new
boundary road crossings to Shenzhen and Zhuhai, two mainland
cities adjoining or near Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the International Union of Public Transport (UIPT)
 for the first time in the Asia-Pacific region, the conference
provides a forum for the exchange of views, sharing of experience,
and tapping of solutions to common problems in urban
transport. Hundreds of delegates from 25 countries take part in
the three-day congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
