<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Banks Purchase Small Foreign Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Commercial banks have not been
able to buy large amounts of U.S. dollars despite the prime
minister's decision to force companies to sell at least 80 percent
of their foreign exchange earnings, the Saigon Times daily
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Ho Chi Minh City Branch of the Central Bank said since the
prime minister's decision took effect, banks have bought around 95
million U.S. dollars, with the City Branch of the Bank for Foreign
Trade of Vietnam accounting for 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
In a latest report sent to the state bank governor, the English
-language daily said, the branch pointed out problems that have
impeded banks' foreign currency purchases and requested the
Central Bank to immediately take action to deal with these.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-invested firms without foreign exchange guarantees will
not be forced to sell foreign funds in their bank accounts, but
they have yet to know what state agencies are responsible for
proving that they are not subject to the decision, said the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it said, public notary offices do not agree to
notarize the copies of contracts written in English, so foreign
companies cannot show sufficient documents to banks in cases where
they are not to sell their foreign exchange holdings.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Saigon Times daily said, it often takes an
applicant a long time to have a document certified.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
