<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Transport Congress Opened in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- An Asian-Pacific congress on
public transport opened here Wednesday to provide a venue for
hundreds of delegates from around the world to share their
insights into promoting the development of efficient urban
transport.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong was chosen to host the regional congress because the
city is an international model for public transport development,
according to the organizer, International Union (Association) of
Public Transport (UITP).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, Anson Chan, Secretary of
Administration of the Special Administrative Region (SAR), briefed
the participants on Hong Kong's urban transport system.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong now boasts a comprehensive, efficient and affordable
urban transport network, ranging from trains to ferries, buses and
trams. Government statistics show that Hong Kong's five franchised
bus operators together carry four million passengers every day,
its suburban railways handles around one million passengers and
its underground railway moves over 2.3 million population a day.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Paul Bailly, president of UITP, highlighted the
preponderance of city transport in his opening remarks, saying:
"Urban transit is part of billions of people's daily lives, so it
plays a key part in society. Its economic role is equally
essential."
</P>
<P>
But he noted: "Mass transit is not an end itself. Its ultimate
purpose is shaped by the city, and its long-standing partner in
working to serve city-dwellers."
</P>
<P>
The UITP president enumerated four challenges for mass transit
in tomorrow's cities -- how to build an accessible city with
tailored networks and transit models, create a pleasant urban
environment, improve service quality and at the same time achieve
economic returns.
</P>
<P>
Hans Rat, Secretary General of UITP, said here Wednesday: "Asia
is the world's largest continent, which has a population of three
billion and covers one third of the global land mass. Keeping such
a densely populated and fast-growing region on the move is a
constant challenge for public transport operators. That is why
UITP organized its first Asia-Pacific Congress in Hong Kong this
year."
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1885, UITP is a worldwide association of urban and
regional transport operators and authorities, with 1,700 members
scattered in some 80 countries and regions in the globe. Its chief
objective is to promote the development of more efficient and
attractive public transport services.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with the three-day conference, the Asia-Pacific City
Transport Exhibition 1998 is held in Hong Kong. Some 80 public
transport operators, automobile manufacturers, and transport
authorities from all over the world display their latest product
designs and technologies there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
