<HEADLINE> Philippines, Malaysia to Resume Defense Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The scheduled defense
cooperation talks between Malaysia and the Philippines will push
through in Manila next month, Philippine presidential spokesman
Jerry Barican said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Citing information from the Malaysian Defense Ministry, he said
the bilateral defense cooperation meeting, originally set for
October 28-30, will take place in Manila on November 8-10.
</P>
<P>
He added that the deferment of the meeting by Malaysia on
October 19 was due to "financial and scheduling constraints" and
has nothing to do with the incident of former Malaysian deputy
prime minister Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was arrested more than two weeks ago and would soon be
tried in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada has called for "the respect
of human rights and due process" for Anwar's trial. However, he
denied that he interfered in Malaysia's internal affairs, saying
what he expressed was only his "personal opinion."
</P>
<P>
There were news reports that Malaysia deferred the scheduled
meeting to show its anger at Estrada's support for Anwar.
</P>
<P>
"The President and Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado have been
apprised of this development. They have also been informed that
the earlier cancellation of the meeting was not in any way related
to the Anwar Ibrahim incident but to financial and scheduling
constraints," Barican said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Philippine Defense Department has started
preparations for the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
