<HEADLINE> China Expects Bumper Corn Harvest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- China anticipates a bumper corn
harvest for this year, with pig production expected to fall and
the decline in corn prices expected to continue, according to
today's issue of Market Daily.
</P>
<P>
Official estimates for the year indicate that corn was planted
on 23.72 million ha, up 2.15 percent on the 1997 figure. Corn
output is expected to hit 115.55 million tons, up 10.8 percent on
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The report indicates the projections fully consider the impact
of heavy summer flooding which hit many parts of China between
June and September. The report also points that flooding affected
beans much more than corn.
</P>
<P>
The increased corn output will further dash hopes for a rise in
corn prices which have been on a downward spiral since the end of
last year, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
The Daily pointed out that many piggeries have expanded
butchering or are selling pigs prematurely and that related
actions will decrease the demand for corn.
</P>
<P>
The paper forecasted further drops in corn prices in the
foreseeable future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
