<HEADLINE> Economic Crisis Could Hurt Environment: UN Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 21 (Xinhua) -- A worrisome by-product of the
ongoing economic crisis in Asia could be environmental degradation
as a result of shifting priorities in government policies, Kayuko
Mizuta, deputy executive secretary of the United Nations Economic
and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP), said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, the low growth figures projected by the World Bank and
the International Monetary Fund for Asian output growth in 1998 do
not take into account any environmental considerations and costs,"
Mizuta said at a three-day meeting on environment and natural
resources, which was inaugurated Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mizuta said the climatic anomalies and natural disasters in
several parts of Asia during the past year had worsened the
economic and social conditions and were related to environmental
degradation caused by human action.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is the first session of the Committee on
Environment and Natural Resources Development, established by
ESCAP in 1997 as part of a revamped program designed to increase
the responsiveness of the regional body to the environmental
challenges facing countries in Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Sunthad Somchevita, representative of the Thai Ministry of
Science, Technology and Environment, said that despite the
economic crisis Thailand had not relaxed its determination to
achieve clean and green environment.
</P>
<P>
Policy measures and enforcement mechanism are being actively
pursued to achieve this objective, he added.
</P>
<P>
Over 100 delegates from various ESCAP member countries, United
Nations agencies, intergovernmental and non-government
organizations are attending the meeting which will end on October
23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
