<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Achieves Great Progress in Human Rights (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official
stated today that the Chinese government and people have made
unremitting efforts to realise the objective of fully enjoying
human rights and have achieved world-renowned progress.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the closing session of the International Symposium
on World Human Rights Towards 21st Century, State Council
Information Office Director Zhao Qizheng said that the symposium
is a rare opportunity for the Chinese people and the people of
other countries to learn from each other and promote mutual
understanding and friendship.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government fully supports the event which was
sponsored by the China Society for Human Rights Studies and the
United Nations Association of China, noted Zhao.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese people have profoundly changed their
destiny during the 20th century. For about 100 years, due to its
poverty and backwardness, China was forced to face hundreds of
wars of aggression and to sign more than 1,000 unequal
treaties. Consequently China's wealth was looted and the lives
and dignity of the Chinese people were subject to appalling
devastation
</P>
<P>
The founding of the People's Republic of China put an end to
the history of oppression and humiliation and the Chinese people
won rudimentary respect and rights as human beings, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of New China, especially the initiation of
reform and opening up to the outside world, the Chinese government
has combined the universal principles of human rights with the
country's actual conditions and persisted in putting the rights to
subsistence and development first and strengthened the building of
democracy and legal system.
</P>
<P>
"The endeavors have pushed forward human rights in an all-round
way and have profoundly changed China's social features," Zhao
stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Achieves Great Progress in Human Rights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Within a short period of 20 years, the number of China's
poverty-stricken people has been reduced by over 200 million and
the majority of people now have enough food and clothing and are
making steady progress towards a well-off life.
</P>
<P>
Remarkable progress has also been made in the development of
democracy which has greatly improved people's awareness of
exercising and enjoying civil and political rights.
</P>
<P>
Zhao went on to say that in the struggle against the worst
floods in decades this summer, the Chinese government did
everything possible to protect some 200 million people in the
flood-stricken areas and ensure that they have food, clean
drinking water, shelter and medical treatment and that the
children in these areas attend schools.
</P>
<P>
The government efforts have helped to reduce to the minimum the
losses of people's lives and property in the floods, he pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
Zhao admitted that China's human rights situation is far from
perfect. Restricted by its natural and historical conditions and
economic development level, it has a long way to go before
realizing modernization and ensure its people fully enjoy human
rights.
</P>
<P>
The 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China
emphasized that the Party would strive to respect and guarantee
human rights and included governing the country according to law
and guarantee human rights in China's cross-century development
strategy.
</P>
<P>
"All these have opened up wide prospects for the development of
China's human rights program into the next century," said Zhao.
</P>
<P>
He noted that for many years other countries have known little
about China's human rights situation, leading to much
misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
Zhao criticized some western people for "judging human rights
issues politically and ideologically" and "regarding a certain
social system as the embodiment of human rights and considering
other social systems and development modes as expressions of
infringement upon human rights."
</P>
<P>
He concluded his speech by pledging that China is sparing no
efforts to build itself into a prosperous, democratic and
culturally advanced country and calling for "maximum understanding
and support" from countries across the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
