<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Nationalize Mineral Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHQNNESBURG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government intends to nationalize South Africa's unexploited
mineral rights in the next 20 years to give black companies
greater access to them, local media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, current mining operations and bona fide intended
operations would be allowed to continue and would not be tampered
with by government, said Minerals and Energy Minister Penuell
Maduna, who released a mining policy white paper and draft
legislation Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Maduna said it was unacceptable to the government that
two-thirds of private ownership of mineral rights was in hands of
the white. But he added that the new policy would not effect
security of tenure for existing mining operations.
</P>
<P>
"The state is not in the mining business. Our intervention is
not aimed at keeping mineral rights in our pockets, but to make
them available and to open up opportunities for all people."
</P>
<P>
The government's long-term objective was for all mineral
rights to vest in the state, but as a transitional measure, a new
system for granting access to mineral rights would apply.
</P>
<P>
Maduna said the white paper mentioned no specific transition
period, but he expected it to be about 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The new system's main aspect would be that the right to
prospect for and to mine all minerals would vest in the state
without infringing on the rights of existing mining right
holders.
</P>
<P>
"The holder of a prospecting right will be entitled to
progress to a mining right on compliance with prescribed criteria
and commitments."
</P>
<P>
During the transitional per)od, holders of mining and mineral
rights would be allowed to register existing or intended
operations under the new system.
</P>
<P>
Maduna said all prospecting information would be submitted to
the state after the completion or abandonment of a particular
prospecting activity.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the prospector retains a mining right, the information
will be released to the public. The freeing of mineral rights
will facilitate greater investment in the mineral industry, also
by small-scale miners."
</P>
<P>
Maduna said mining on a limited scale could increase
competitiveness and help to create jobs.
</P>
<P>
He said foreign investment in the mining sector would also be
encouraged.
</P>
<P>
Legislation to put the new policy into effect would be
introduced after next year's general election, Maduna said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
