<HEADLINE> S. African Firm Aims at No.1 Internet Provider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's leading
cellular network operator Vodacom Tuesday launched its
53-million-U.S. Dollar Internet service, which allowc Internet
access through prepaid vouchers.
</P>
<P>
Vodacom, one of South Africa's two dominating cellular network
providers, said it planned to be the country's largest Internet
service provider in just two months, Business Day rfported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But becoming a significant player by Christmas is a tall
order, considering the 150 registered Internet service providers
and an estimated 750,000 Internet users in the country, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The aggressive deadline gives Vodacom 10 weeks to outsell
South Africa's largest access providers, UUNet Internet Africa,
with 80,000 dial-up users, and MWeb, with 58,000 dial-up clients.
</P>
<P>
Vodacom said it was not worried by the cenge, as it did
not see a very competitive market in the Internet field.
</P>
<P>
Vodacom chief executive officer Alan Knott-Craig said there
were still about 4.3 million users to be signed up for Internet
access across the coubtry, and Vodacom's newly-launched Yebonet
wanted the lion's share.
</P>
<P>
Vodacom will offer prepaid Internet access using its cellular
phone vouchers, which were already available from retail outlets
across the country.
</P>
<P>
Voda#om said Yebonet would target consumers aged between 16
and 25 and the main source of news on the website was from South
Africa's leading newspaper group, the Independent Group.
</P>
<P>
However, some of South Africa's major Internet service
providers said Vodacom was being extremely optimistic. They
doubted a new player like Vodacom would dominate the market in a
few months, as the subscriber base was pretty well entrenched.
</P>
</TEXT>
