<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Risky Investment: A New Way To Use Chinese Research Findings (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Xu Xingtang
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Risky investments have been a
popular topic among Chinese financiers for the past few months as
a new way to raise scientific and technological development funds
that can greatly help make commercial use of research findings.
</P>
<P>
These investments use money for research and development of
technology and products that contain a high degree of risk but
that have a high rate of return.
</P>
<P>
In March, when the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC) met in Beijing, a
proposal for a risky investment mechanism was a major bill set
before the conference, one that caught the immediate attention of
both government and society.
</P>
<P>
The Vice-Chairman of the National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, Prof. Cheng Siwei, has been studying risky
investments for many years and says that they have good prospects
in China and that the time is ripe for them.
</P>
<P>
He says that they are an effective method of supporting
research commercialization and can help the development of new
industries and provide new use of public capital to benefit
national economic growth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Risky Investment: A New Way to Use Chinese Research Findings (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Every year China has more than 10,000 new research findings and
over 20,000 patents, but fewer than 10 percent can be put to
practical use and the others withered away because of lack of
funds or for other reasons.
</P>
<P>
Since the opening up and reforms started some 20 years ago,
high-tech industries have made big strides and there are 52
state-level high-tech development zones and approximately 20,000
high-tech enterprises across the country, providing a good
environment for developing research results. When adequate
investment is available, it can generate good returns.
</P>
<P>
The amount of bank deposits in the country has been more than 5
trillion yuan for a long time, and once a well-regulated risky
investment mechanism is established, these funds can be channeled
into the technology sector to develop emerging enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has paid special attention to high-tech
industries and has a series of policies and measures that guide
investment into them. Since 1984, banks have played a major role
in providing science and technology loans that have gone from some
15 million yuan at that time to more than 8 billion yuan in 1994.
</P>
<P>
A large number of risky investment companies have emerged and
there are more than 80 science and technology trust companies,
risky investment companies, and related credit cooperatives with a
combined investment portfolio of 3 billion yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Risky Investment: A New Way to Use Chinese Research Findings (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But, analysts say, this is not a risk capital industry because
the investment still uses traditional investment methods of
government capital allocation, and funds follow government
policies. In nature it is still government investment, and the
government undertakes the investment risks as well.
</P>
<P>
They say that China has appropriate conditions for funds,
technology, and personnel to develop risky investment and that
what the government should do is to accelerate financial system
reforms and encourage risky investment.
</P>
<P>
Ma Zhaoming, of Jiangsu Securities, says that a government
mechanism is needed to develop the business and should include
government subsidies, bank loans with government warranties, and
preferential tax measures.
</P>
<P>
A prominent economist from the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, Wang Guogang, says that China should build a multi-tier
capital market to promote risky investment and an ideal way is to
set up a second securities market to serve emerging enterprises
that can provide fund-raising channels for privately-run,
high-tech enterprises that have difficulties qualifying for the
A-shares market.
</P>
<P>
Cheng says China's risky investment business is still at a
primary stage and that all conditions must be taken into full
account when designing an investment strategy.
</P>
<P>
He proposes first, setting up risky investment advisory and
management companies responsible for appraising projects and
recommending them to investors; secondly, establishing risky
investment funds within 3 to 5 years to raise funds from domestic
and overseas sources and, thirdly, opening the second security
market within 5 to 10 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The World Has No Choice But to Act  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tay is a law professor at the University of Sydney and serves
as the director of institution's Center for Asian and Pacific
Law. She is also member of the International Legal Service
Advisory Council. Professor Tay's wide area of interests include
jurisprudence, the socialist legal system and theory, as well as
the Chinese legal system and comparative law. She was awarded the
Order of Australia in 1986 for her contributions to legal studies.
</P>
<P>
Professor Tay said the trend towards globalization has made us
neighbors subject to mutual fate. We must cooperate in saving
lives, alleviating suffering, protecting values and sustaining
faith. Modern technology allows us to respond far more quickly to
human rights concerns. Television images of battlefield smoke
should always remind us the urgent need to act.
</P>
<P>
Looking ahead to the 21st century, Professor Tay said that the
lingering crisis has led to the emergence of new challenges. War,
famine and loss of educational opportunities continue to be major
problems and the most vulnerable social groups need a helping hand
to protect their rights. Accepting the responsibilities of
"neighborhoods" in regional formations will be a key factor in
tackling human rights problems. Relief and assistance for basic
needs must be met and technical assistance must be provided. The
rule of law and the role of government must be
promoted. Neglecting human rights issues because of economic
setbacks is a highly risky issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
