<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi said Wednesday that his country would continue to help
Africa with its development.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi made the remarks during a 30-minute meeting with
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan, which was held before the end
of the three-day African aid conference.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that an action plan adopted at the conference
Wednesday would be a model for a future development plan in
Africa, Japanese Foreign Ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived in Japan on Tuesday to attend the Second
Tokyo International Conference on African Development, emphasized
the importance of creating actual change in the lives of African
people by transforming the action plan into real actions.
</P>
<P>
Annan welcomed Obuchi's promise that Japan's support for
African development would not merely end with the Tokyo meeting,
but would continue as a long-term process, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi and Annan also exchanged views on the reform of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Annan will conclude his three-day visit to Japan on Thursday,
after holding talks with Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko
Komura. 
