<HEADLINE> Japan Committed to Close Ties with S. Africa: Mbeki Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Japan has pledged to keep
its economic and development relationship with South Africa
despite his country's financial stisis, local daily Business Day
quoted Deputy President Thabo Mbiek as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who is visiting Japan, Tuesday told a press conference
in Tokyo after talks with Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
that the Japanese government was committed to helping Africa and
enhancing bilateral ties with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki is attending the 2nd Tokyo International Conference on
African Development (Ticad II) in the Japanese capital. He
visited Japan in April this year when Obuchi was still foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi had proposed that South Africa and Japan should meet as
soon as possible to discuss the practical implementation of an
agenda for action which wi|l be adopted at the ongoing Ticad.
</P>
<P>
The agenda aims to halve the number of Africa's extremely poor
country by 2015.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki dismissed perceptions that Ticad II was yet another
talkshop, saying that Japan, one of the largest economic power in
the world, was so focused on Africa that could not be ignored.
</P>
<P>
Japan, along with the United Nations and the Global Coalition
for Africa, is sponsoring Ticad II, a follow-up to the first
conference held in Tokyo in 1993 in which South Africa only
participated as an observer.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki also welcomed Obuchi's statement on Monday that Japan
was giving serious consideration to increasing its debt relief
program. He described this as a "very welcome flexibility"
because Japan had historically been more orthodox in its
approach to debt relief.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Bank, African debt stands at about 170
billion U.S. Dollars, of which 45 billion Dollars is owed to the
bank.
</P>
<P>
Japan's new attitude would have important implications for
calls for debt relief, as the country had an important voice in
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund, Mbeki said.
</P>
</TEXT>
