<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 09:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Media Say Peace Deal is Expected Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli news media said on
Wednesday that Israeli and Palestinian negotiators, who are
holding talks at the seclusive Wye Plantation outside Washington,
will reach a peace deal soon.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post newspaper quoted a senior member of the
Israeli delegation as saying that the bargaining is "gruesome,"
but "there is a good chance we will clinch a deal at the last
minute."
</P>
<P>
Local daily Haaretz said sources from all three sides
concurred that after five days of deadlock, the mood turned
upbeat on Tuesday and an agreement might be finalized on
Wednesday or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A report by Israel Television Channel 1 said that a signing
ceremony is also planned for Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz added that one important area of progress is in the
realm of security, where sources said there is convergence on
areas of principle, although some drafting remains to be done.
</P>
<P>
And Israel is now apparently prepared to accept a Palestinian
counter-terrorism "work plan" put forward by the U.S. Central
Intelligence Agency Director George Tenet a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Israeli negotiators also explored possible compromises with
Palestinian officials on establishing a safe passage between the
West Bank and Gaza, and constructing a Palestinian seaport in
Gaza, and there are signs that an accord has been reached on the
Dahaniya Airport.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of a unilateral Palestinian declaration of
statehood on May 4 next year, the U.S. is trying to defuse a
potential explosion by agreeing to discuss final status issues at
a later "event," on the eve of the May 4th deadline, to replace it.
</P>
<P>
But disagreements still remain on several issues, including
the third Israeli pullback, a "time-out" for Jewish settlement
expansion and the Israeli insistence on convening the Palestinian
National Council to delete the call for Israel's destruction in
the 1964 Palestinian Charter.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post said that Israel has offered a "partial
agreement" that would leave out the most contentious points, such
as the extent and timing of the third withdrawal. But the
Palestinians are insisting on a full agreement, saying they must
get commitments now.
</P>
<P>
The Yediot Aharonot newspaper noted that Jordan's King Hussein
arrived at the Wye Plantation on Tuesday and his joining the
mediation efforts would give an extra boost to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Wye Plantation summit began last Thursday and was extended
twice with no sign of progress until Tuesday. The Israeli and
Palestinian leaders will continue talks on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
