<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The World Has No Choice But to Act (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- "Cries of distress leave no
choice but to act," according to Alice Tay, president of the
Australian Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
Tay made the comment today at the International Symposium on
World Human Rights Towards the 21st Century.
</P>
<P>
Professor Tay said that opportunities for rebuilding societies
and communities suffering from destruction and loss are just as
great today as they were 50 years ago when the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights was signed. Opportunities are
accompanied by various crises such as localized wars, and the
revival of racial, religious and ideological conflicts which have
brought continuing misery to the world. However, significant
differences between today and 50 years ago include the fact that
many more nations, organizations and individuals have joined
together to build better societies.
</P>
<P>
Tay addressed China's human rights record by noting that the
ideals of human rights are not only self-evident, but also serve
the mutual purpose of all nations. However, pluralized social and
historical backgrounds determine different starting point for
human rights record. Therefore, we should focus more on
aspirations, rather than achievements when evaluating human rights
records. China has a long history of feudalism and wartime
turbulence and quite naturally shoulders imperative responsibility
in this respect. The fact that China recently signed a number of
human rights conventions represents the nation's desire to keep
its sincere promise to the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
