<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Americans Hope Government Helps Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Two thirds of Americans
believe that the U.S. government should help the poor, preferably
through education and job training rather than "income transfers,"
said a Gallup social survey released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 45 percent of respondents say the government should
tax the rich to help level the playing field.
</P>
<P>
The latest Gallup survey questioned 5,001 people from April 23
through May 21 and focused on the questions of American's "have"
and "have nots", in light of concerns that the country is growing
more divided between the rich and poor, said Frank Newport, editor
in chief of the Gallup Poll.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that almost two thirds feel that money and
wealth in the United States have not been evenly distributed.
</P>
<P>
"What's clear in our data is that Americans appear to want some
reduction in the degree of economic inequality," said Jack Ludwig,
a Gallup senior scientist who ran the survey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
