<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 08:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Settlers Protest Against Wye Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli settlers were holding
protests in the West Bank Wednesday after hearing the news that an
agreement is to be reached soon in the Mideast peace talks.
</P>
<P>
A large number of Jewish settlers gathered from Wednesday
morning near the settlement of Beit El, north of the West Bank
city of Ramallah, to curse the ongoing talks at Wye Plantation
outside Washington which reportedly would lead to Israel's further
troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish settlers have blocked the Ramallah-Nablus main
highway and set up road barriers on it, a local Palestinian
reporter told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace talks concluded its sixth day discussions
Tuesday. To help achieve a breakthrough, U.S. President Bill
Clinton canceled his fund-raising trip to California to join talks
with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, King Hussein of Jordan, who was undergoing cancer
treatment at the Mayo Clinic in Minnesota, was also called by
Clinton to come to the Plantation to contribute to the mediation
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media reports said progress was made during Tuesday's
talks on several key issues, security in particularly, but they
remain divided on the third Israeli pullback, the expansion of
settlement, the scope of Palestinian prisoners' release and the
Israeli insistence on convening the Palestinian National Council
to delete the call for Israel's destruction in the 1964
Palestinian Charter.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, the reports said, an agreement signing ceremony is
expected shortly, possibly on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
As the Wye Plantation peace talks moved on, Israeli settler
leaders held an "emergency meeting" Tuesday in Jerusalem and
decided to be prepared to block 15 key roads leading to the West
Bank and Gaza Strip the minute an agreement is initiated at Wye
Plantation.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's demonstrations near Beit El were apparently part of
the protest activities organized by the settlers to vent their
anger over Netanyahu's possible concessions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 17 members of the right-wing Land of Israel Front of
the Knesset (parliament), have threatened that they will vote
against the government if Netanyahu retreats from his hardline
positions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
