<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts on Human Rights Challenges in 21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Scholars attending the
International Symposium on World Human Rights Towards the 21st
Century in Beijing today agreed that it's going to take a great
effort to promote human rights and free human beings from wars and
turbulence in the new century.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the symposium, which is sponsored by the China
Society for Human Rights Studies and the China UN Association, is
to discuss developing human rights in the 21st century and to
commemorate the 50th anniversary of the Universal Declaration on
Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
Virendra Dayal, former Deputy Secretary-General of the United
Nations, said that protecting human rights means not only keeping
world peace and security, but also ensuring sustained development
globally and within all countries.
</P>
<P>
"Efforts must be made to establish complete relationship among
peace, development and rights, and to keep the efforts coherent
and reasonable, there must be impartial and just policies in all
fields," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting the changing content of human rights along with the
deepening understanding of the rights, the former UN official said
that the world must make a greater effort to consolidate human
rights developments and to increase women's rights.
</P>
<P>
After two world wars, the United Nations Charter was adopted in
1945. Three years later, the Universal Declaration of Human Rights
defined the relation between interior peace in one country and
human rights with legal protection.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad Khalifa, a former chairman of the UN Social Development
Commission, said that human rights issues are now mixed up with
global conflicts in politics and ideology, and that one of the
most important things is to avoid social upheavals caused by the
increasing imbalance of social forces and marginalization.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zaibang, an international relations scholar, said that
poverty will remain a serious problem in the 21st century and the
existing international economic order is becoming an obstacle to
the development of human rights.
</P>
<P>
In international affairs, power politics and violation of human
rights in various forms will continue to present obstacles to the
effective protection of human rights in various countries, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Siew Nyoke Chow, a Malaysian scholar, expressed the opinions of
ASEAN member countries about the current human rights situation in
the world.
</P>
<P>
She said that for many Asian countries, the unfair and unequal
global structure controlled by some Western countries does much
more harm to the economic, social, cultural and political rights
of mankind than any single country does to human rights.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discounts Attract American Online Shoppers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 20 Xinhua) -- Discounted pricing is the
most important way to make the American online shoppers become
online buyers, according to a study released on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The study found that those who have access to the Internet but
yet to make purchases online are still hesitant to initiate
transaction, citing price, not payment security, as a primary
concern.
</P>
<P>
They were less likely to make an initial purchase soon. One of
the main reasons for the reluctance is the barrier of price. Most
of them said that greater discounts online will spark buying
behavior, said the study, which was based on an extensive set of
consumer surveys.
</P>
<P>
The study was jointly conducted by Jupiter Communications, a
new media research firm, and NFO Worldwide, a provider of customer
and syndicated marketing information services.
</P>
<P>
A significant 35 percent of the 60 million U.S. online
population did purchase a product or service in the last year and
were satisfied with their shopping experience, the study said.
</P>
<P>
However, it went to say that although lowering prices may help
many transact online, it should not be the only outcome that
online marketers depend on. Consumers are increasingly relying on
online information sources to drive their off-line purchases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
