<HEADLINE> Profit Loss Brings America Bank President Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 20 (Xinhua) -- David Coulter, president of
Bank of America, the largest in the United States, announced his
resignation Tuesday, following the bank's huge drop in the
third-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
"The decision was extremely difficult for me, both personally
and professionally," he said in a bank's news release, without
explaining why.
</P>
<P>
Hugh McColl, the bank's chairman and CEO, said in a brief
statement that "it is very painful for me personally to accept his
resignation."
</P>
<P>
On October 15, the bank reported a profit falling by half to
893 million U.S. dollars in the third quarter from 1.77 billion
dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The sag in profits was the result in large part of the carnage
in the bank's worldwide trading of stocks, bonds and currencies
and losses in such troubled places as Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Bank of America is the result of a merger between NationsBank
and BankAmerica. Coulter was formerly chairman and CEO of
BankAmerica and expected to succeed the 63-year-old McColl as the
new bank's chairman. But a decision he made cost both his old and
future jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
