<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Eradication Contributes to Human Rights Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Human rights experts attending
the ongoing International Symposium on World Human Rights Towards
the 21st Century said today that eradicating poverty represents the
most important human rights issue requiring immediate attention.
</P>
<P>
Professor Li Tiecheng from the Beijing Languages and Culture
College pointed out that the "gap between the rich and poor is
widening, and the seriousness of social problems such as the
unequal distribution of resources is increasing.
</P>
<P>
No country, large or small, can separate itself from
population, environmental, economic, social and military issues
existing in the world, Li said, adding that poverty, disease and
regional conflicts affect all parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 issue of the UNDP Human Development Report shows that
the gap between rich and poor countries has expanded. Statistics
provided in the report show that there are over one billion
people lack basic living necessities.
</P>
<P>
Li said that all people truly concerned about human rights
should focus their attention to the poverty-stricken people who
account for a fifth of the world's total population. "They not
only need sympathy, but also actual work and action," said Li.
</P>
<P>
Park Sang-Yong, a member of the United Nations Subcommission on
Preventing Discrimination and Protecting Minorities, said we must
exhibit greater concern for poverty-stricken people, including the
1.3 billion people who survive on less than one U.S. dollar a day.
</P>
<P>
Park, a former diplomat in the Repubic of Korea (ROK), pointed
out that there is no doubt that eradicating poverty is the
greatest challenge facing human beings. Poverty constitutes a
great threat to the rights and interests of women and children in
particular.
</P>
<P>
He called on all governments and all nongovernmental
organizations to pay close attention to worldwide poverty, and
make outstanding contributions to guaranteeing the rights of
ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
Professor Li Tiecheng noted that resolving issues regarding
rights to subsistence and development will be the major challenge
in the coming century and also the lifeline of the human rights
cause.
</P>
<P>
He also suggested that the United Nations should properly
handle the relationship between protecting human rights and
respecting the sovereignty. "Human rights protection will mainly
rely on the efforts of sovereign states," according to Li. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0174 </DOCNO>
