<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam, Japan Sign Technical Cooperation Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam and Japan have signed a
technical cooperation agreement, the English daily Vietnam News
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, a result of negotiations starting in 1996, was
signed in Hanoi on Tuesday by Vietnam's Minister of Planning and
Investment Tran Xuan Gia and Japanese Ambassador to Vietnam
Katsunari Suzuki.
</P>
<P>
The agreement defines obligations of each side in implementing
non-refundable aid programs under the form of technical
cooperation funded by the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Japan will provide technical help
to Vietnam, including the dispatching of Japanese experts,
accepting Vietnamese trainees and the provision of equipment.
</P>
<P>
Since the resumption of official development assistance (ODA)
for Vietnam in November 1992, the ODA budgets granted to Vietnam
by the Japanese government have accounted for 32 percent of the
total pledged by international communities. Japan has been
Vietnam's biggest ODA provider for the past six consecutive years,
in terms of preferential credits as well as non-refundable aid.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government grants non-refundable aid worth 100
million U.S. dollars each year on average. Such aid has been
provided to the Vietnamese government to upgrade and build social
welfare facilities to promote and balance budgets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Insists on Peaceful Solution to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 21 (Xinhua) -- President Slobodan Milosevic
said here Tuesday that despite the provocation by the armed ethnic
Albanians, the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and the Republic of
Serbia insist that the Kosovo crisis be solved by political and
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic made the remarks while meeting with NATO's Supreme
Commander Allied Forces in Europe General Wesley Clark and
U.S. mediator for Kosovo Christopher Hill, the Tanjug news agency
Tanjug reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came after the separatist Kosovo Liberation Army
attacked Serbian police during Belgrade's military pullback last
week from Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
Separatist guerrillas in Kosovo have repeatedly attacked Serb
police, killing five and wounding nine, Kosovo Information Bureau
Director Bosko Drobnjak said in an interview with Xinhua. Two
journalists from the Tanjug news agency were also founded missing.
</P>
<P>
Clark, who arrived in Belgrade on Tuesday evening, was
following up a deal reached on October 13 by U.S. envoy to
Yugoslavia Richard Holbrooke aimed at averting NATO air strikes on
the east European country.
</P>
<P>
The strikes are currently in check until October 27 when NATO
will judge whether Milosevic has complied with the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav president has agreed to permit surveillance by
non-combat planes and a deployment of 2,000 observers from the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe to ensure the
withdrawal of the Serb forces from Kosovo. 
</P>
