<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Egyptian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Egyptian newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Al Ahram:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak received a phone call
Tuesday from U.S. President Bill Clinton on the lastest
developments of the Palestinian-Israeli talks and bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
During the 10-minute call, Clinton briefed Mubarak on the
progress of the peace talks and the sticking issues.
</P>
<P>
Al Akhbar:
</P>
<P>
-- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa Tuesday met with his
Tajik counterpart Nazarov Talbak on enhancing bilateral trade and
economic relations.
</P>
<P>
Talbak expressed his country's desire to benefit from Egypt's
economic reform experience.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has pursued successful economic reforms since the early
1990s underpinned by deregulation and privatization.
</P>
<P>
Al Gomhuria:
</P>
<P>
-- Moussa is to hold talks Wednesday morning with chief
delegates of the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS)
participating in the first conference on boosting economic ties.
</P>
<P>
The five-day conference, which will open Wednesday, will
explore ways to promote Egyptian-CIS trade and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Gazette:
</P>
<P>
-- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides arrived in Cairo
Tuesday night on a three-day visit, during which he will convey a
message to Mubarak from Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-Cypriot talks will deal with a number of regional
issues and ways of solving the protracted Cyprus issue in line
with the relevant U.N. resolutions. 
</P>
