<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise For Fourth Consecutive Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose for the fourth
straight trading day in Tokyo Wednesday with the key Nikkei index
recovering to 14,000 level, on news report that Industrial Bank of
Japan (IBJ) will seek a capital injection from the government.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 408.28 points, or 2.96
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 14,216.33, its highest
finish since September 14 when it marked 14,227.37.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, advanced 28.81 points or 2.76 percent to
1,071.83.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section mushroomed to an estimated 861
million shares, nearly twice this year's daily average of 450.40
million shares.
</P>
<P>
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan was the day's most heavily
traded issue.
</P>
<P>
News that IBJ is raising its hand was the driving force of
Wednesday's market, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Bank shares charged ahead for a fourth straight day as feelings
spread that other major banks in need of capital may join IBJ in
applying to a government-designed 60 trillion yen (about 517.2
billion dollars) bailout scheme, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,344 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
overwhelmed losers 966 to 228, with 101 issues ending unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
