<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Urges U.S. to Remove Embargo Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Wednesday urged
the United States to immediately remove its embargo on imports of
wild harvested shrimps from Malaysia and several other countries
in the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
The call is in line with the recommendation of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) which concluded that the U.S. embargo on the
import of certain shrimp and shrimp products was inconsistent with
WTO provisions, Malaysia's Ministry of International Trade and
Industry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's export of shrimps was adversely affected by the U.S.
trade embargo which came into effect in May 1996, the ministry
said, adding since then Malaysia's exports of wild harvested
shrimps to the U.S. were significantly diminished as only aqua
cultured shrimps were imported from Malaysia last year while there
was no export of wild harvested shrimps.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's total shrimps export to the U.S. fell to 1.47
million U.S. dollars in 1997 from 9.1 million U.S. dollars in
1995, according to the ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Scientists Find Cause for Women Losing Babies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Scientists have
found "the real cause" for women who suffer multiple miscarriages.
</P>
<P>
Until now it is thought many fetuses die in the womb because
clots in the mother's blood supply block the flow of nutrients to
the unborn child. But a team of NZ scientists headed by Dr. Larry
Chamley, of Auckland University's Department of Obstetrics, has
discovered that women who suffer repeated miscarriages or
stillborn babies produce a particular antibody, called
anticardiolipin, which interferes with the growth of vital cells
in the placenta called trophoblasts, the New Zealand Press
Association (NZPA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the team, these cells effectively kickstart
placental growth by invading the arteries of the uterus and
increasing bloodflow to the placenta so the baby can grow. But the
anticardiolipin antibody interferes with the placenta's formation,
destroying the baby's chances of survival to full term.
</P>
<P>
The team's discovery also questioned the effectiveness of
existing treatments where anticoagulants are given to at-risk
women to prevent blood clots forming, the NZPA said.
</P>
<P>
"We produced antibodies in the laboratory which mimic these
women's antibodies and we then put them with trophoblast cell
lines," Dr. Chamley said. "We showed they actually stopped the
trophoblast cells from growing, which means they can't form the
placenta. They effectively prevent the pregnancy from working."
</P>
<P>
Dr. Chamley's team hopes the discovery can lead to the
development of new drugs which can spare women the heartbreak of
repeated miscarriages, the NZPA said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Wildfires Blaze out of Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Wildfires, pushed by strong
winds, Tuesday continued to rage out of control in several areas
throughout California, local news reports said.
</P>
<P>
The fire in Fillmore, Ventura County, about 112 kilometers
north of Los Angeles, has consumed 6,500 acres of brush and trees
in mountainous terrain.
</P>
<P>
"The fire was 55 percent contained and should be surrounded by
Friday night, said Ventura Country fire Capt. Michael Lindbery,
adding that more than 900 firefighters are keeping the biggest of
the blazes away from homes.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 kilometers further north, a 3,300-acre blaze in dense
brush in the remote Los Padres National Forest, also in Ventura
Country, was 40 percent contained. Reports said more than 1,100
firefighters are battling fire there.
</P>
<P>
"We will take advantage of the nighttime and try to get some
things established," Lindbery said. "But when the east wind comes
up in the morning, it makes things difficult."
</P>
<P>
The third wildfire has burned 100 acres near Camino in northern
California, where official evacuated 50 homes as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, worse wildfires claimed lives and burned
tens of thousands of brush and trees in the state.
</P>
<P>
October traditionally sees the start of the southern California
fire season as hot winds known as Santa Anas blow in from the
desert.
</P>
<P>
But officials fear that this year's fire season might be worse
than usual because storms spurred by the El Nino weather
phenomenon that soaked the area earlier this year have spurred
lush growth of thick underbrush. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
