<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prison Inmates in New Zealand Reach 5,300 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 21 (Xinhua) -- About 5,300 people were in
New Zealand prisons and 47,000 were given community-based
sentences in the past 12 months, the Dominion newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted the annual report of the
New Zealand Corrections Department as saying that in the past 10
years the imprisonment rate has increased by 58 percent and the
prison population is expected to reach 6,000 by the year 2002.
</P>
<P>
The department spent 350 million New Zealand dollars (186
million U.S. dollars) on managing prisoners in the past year, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Disturbances during the year included a hostage incident, a
riot, suicides and 84 escapes, it added.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Corrections Department employs about 4,000
part- and full-time staff, and operates 16 prisons, 16 community
probation service offices and 220 service sites, eight
psychological service offices, three special treatment units and a
head office.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Government intends to acquire five new prison
sites to meet a forecast 22 percent prison population increase by
2020, according to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
