<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Misgivings Prevail Over Kosovo Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRISTINA, Yugoslavia, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Although the
situation in Kosovo has quieted down following the conclusion of
the Milosevic-Holbrooke agreement, pessimism remains prevalent
over the prospects of an ultimate settlement of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Kosovo Information Bureau Director
Bosko Drobnjak said that the October 13 peace deal had headed off
an impending armed intervention by the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, but the situation in Kosovo remained unstable.
</P>
<P>
During Belgrade's military pullback last week, separatist
guerrillas in Kosovo have repeatedly attacked Serb policemen, with
five killed and nine wounded, Drobnjak said. Two journalists from
the Tanjug news agency were found missing.
</P>
<P>
The official said that despite a worldwide acclaim for the
peace deal reached between the Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic and U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke, the Albanian leaders
in Kosovo still refused to accept it. "That is the biggest
obstacle to the solution of the Kosovo crisis," he noted.
</P>
<P>
What was most important, the official said, was to create a
peaceful atmosphere for the restart of negotiations concerning the
future of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that if the Albanian representatives
continued to reject dialogues and negotiations, the Serbian
government will act to handle the crisis in accordance with the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
He accused the West of giving unprincipled protection to the
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo, which, he said, had whetted the
ambitions of the Albanian extremists to split the country and
rendered the situation in the region more complicated.
</P>
<P>
He said some Western countries wanted to take control of Kosovo
for its strategic importance. Therefore, they had been trying to
provoke and get involved in the conflicts, and did not balk at
intervention by force.
</P>
<P>
He said there was hope for a final settlement of the Kosovo
crisis only if the West stopped interfering in Yugoslavia's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
In a separate interview with Xinhua, Fehmi Agani, chief of the
five-member negotiation team of the ethic Albanians also expressed
concerns over the fate of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He said the ethnic Albanians accepted the Milosevic-Holbrooke
agreement and were willing to negotiate with the Yugoslav
government over Kosovo's future on condition that the status of
Kosovo be decided upon first.
</P>
<P>
Agani said the Albanians were willing to remain in Yugoslavia
if they were granted a status like Serbia and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
He said his party, the League of Democracy of Kosovo (LDK),
realized that "it is impossible for Kosovo to gain full
independence in the near future."
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the peace deal struck a week ago, he said that his
party, the largest political party in Kosovo, supported it and
welcomes the OSCE mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace accord, a 2,000-strong verification force of
the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
will be deployed in Kosovo to ensure the withdrawal of Serb forces
and the safe return of tens of thousands of refugees and displaced
people.
</P>
<P>
"But we haven't signed the agreement yet because the status of
Kosovo has not been settled," Agani said.
</P>
<P>
Softening the tone of the ethnic Albanians who insist on full
independence, Agani said he was willing to settle the Kosovo
crisis within Yugoslavia, but not inside Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanian leaders in Kosovo earlier rejected a political
solution to the dispute, which promised an election within nine
months and the set-up of a police force in Kosovo reflecting the
ethnic make-up in the province.
</P>
<P>
Agani, also LDK vice-chairman, said he was ready to start
negotiations with the Serb government on the future of Kosovo in
which 90 percent of the two million people are ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to discuss the proposals with the Serbian
government," he added, but giving no date for new talks.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that he was pessimistic about the prospect of a
political settlement of the Kosovo crisis within Yugoslavia
because the the positions of the two sides were far apart.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav leaders have never backed down on their position
that Kosovo is the internal affairs of Serbia and therefore must
be settled within the Serbian Republic that makes up the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia with Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
Even Western countries are opposed to the full independence of
Kosovo. There are fears that ethnic Albanians living in
neighboring Macedonia, where they make up a quarter of the
population, will also revolt and demand joining a greater Albania,
thus plunging the region into further turmoils.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to accept an interim agreement to stay for a
period of time in Yugoslavia, but after perhaps three years, there
must be a referendum which will decide the fate of Kosovo," Agani
said.
</P>
<P>
The Albanian chief negotiator said that although formal talks
with the Serbs have been suspended, unofficial engagement and
indirect talks with the Serb government have never come to a
standstill. "We wish to talk with them, but the talks must begin
without any preconditions and in a peaceful atmosphere," he added.
</P>
<P>
When asked about whether the radical Kosovo Liberation Army
(KLA) will accept the plan to stay in Yugoslavia, he said he
believed if they could figure out a political solution acceptable
to most Albanians, the KLA would also agree with it.
</P>
<P>
The KLA, whose sole goal is independence for Kosovo, had fought
a seven-month war with the Serbian forces before a ceasefire 10
days ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
