<HEADLINE> Central Chinese Overseas Investment Use </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investment has become
a major force in economic growth in central China's Hunan
province, Deputy-Governor He Tongxin said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
More than 4,600 foreign-funded enterprises have been approved
in Hunan in the past few years, involving 5.1 billion U.S.
dollars worth of investment, and their output accounted for six
percent of the province's GDP in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 3.1 billion dollars of direct overseas investment has
been utilized, while many multinationals are playing a role in
changing the local industrial structure, the official said.
</P>
<P>
About half of the Sino-foreign joint ventures are in
production, employing 330,000 local people.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, they exported 398 million dollars worth of products,
accounting for 17 percent of the province's total.
</P>
<P>
The deputy-governor said that overseas investors have also been
participating in local infrastructure projects. Overseas
investment accounted for 32 percent of the investment in the
province's energy and transportation sectors in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
