<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholars Discuss Human Rights in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The human rights situation in
China has become one of the focuses of discussion at an
international symposium on human rights which began here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese enjoy a high level of economic, political,
cultural, and individual rights that were unimaginable 20 years
ago, Prof. Norbert Meienberger of Zurich University said at the
International Symposium on World Human Rights toward the 21st
Century.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, sponsored jointly by the China Society for Human
Rights Studies and the China UN Association, has drawn scholars
from China and 26 other countries from Asia, Africa, Latin
America, Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
Meienberger, who visited China for several times in the 1970s,
said some Westerners know little about China's past, and neither
do they know much about its present.
</P>
<P>
They usually reprimand China for its human rights situation
from their own political stand, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Even so, China still has a long way to go in improving human
rights because it was ravaged by years of war and turmoil, said
Alice Erh-soon Tay, president of the Human Rights and Equal
Opportunity Commission, Australia, who saw the symposium as a
forum for people from different countries to freely discuss human
rights.
</P>
<P>
Aware of the situation, the Chinese government has showed its
determination to development human rights in the country by
signing a series of international conventions on human rights in
recent years, she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, held to commemorate the 50th anniversary of the
Universal Declaration on Human Rights, sent such a message to the
world again that China will go further in its human rights and
democracy, said David Dubois, a Sinologist and professor at the
University of Massachusetts, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Sharing similar views with Meienberger, Dubois added that
certain attacks on China's human rights record may be attributed
to worry about China's growing economic strength.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market for Information Appliances to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 20 (Xinhua) -- The global market for
information appliances is "on the verge of explosive growth," said
a U.S. market analysis firm.
</P>
<P>
The market is expected to climb from three million units in
1997 and nearly six million this year to an overwhelming 55.7
million in 2002 worldwide, registering a 76 percent annual growth
rate between 1998 and 2002, according to a report by the
International Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
Information appliances are household or office devices that can
be plugged into common public or private networks.
</P>
<P>
In late 1998, the industry has begun to coalesce around key
platforms and specific solution partnership initiatives. On the
down side are network computers and screenphones. But the lion's
share of the information appliance momentum has moved toward
internet TV, gaming devices and smart handhelds, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Internet smart handheld devices show the greatest promise for
deployment on an absolute unit shipment basis. However, IDC said,
these products primarily lie in the corporate domain, with many
purchased directly by corporate funds. As a result, these
handhelds will drop out of the top ranking and get closer to the
bottom of unit shipments for consumer-used items.
</P>
<P>
Internet gaming devices also have great potential, with the
growth accelerating from 848,000 units in 1998 to almost 15
million in 2002.
</P>
<P>
Internet TVs represent a hot bed of innovation, the report
said. They will quickly become the next largest category of
information appliances, generating 1.4 million units in 1998, 4.3
million in 1999 and over 11 million units at the turn of the
millennium. At present, Internet TV services use a set-top box
that connects the TV to a modem and telephone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
