<HEADLINE> Northern China Oil Production Not Affected by Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Daqing Oilfield, China's
largest oil production base in the northeast, will not be affected
by this year's floods and will meet the year's production quota of
55.7 million tons of oil on schedule, Mayor Yang Xin has promised.
</P>
<P>
Daqing, which was also built as China's largest petrochemical
production base, has 30 million sq km of oilfields and recorded
an annual production of 50 million tons of oil for 22 years. It now
processes 14 million tons of crude oil annually.
</P>
<P>
The city was hit by severe flooding this summer, but the
principal production oil wells were not affected thanks to the
hard work of soldiers and civilians.
</P>
<P>
Only two percent of the oilfield's daily production capacity
was affected even at the most severe flood levels, according to
Yang, mayor of Daqing which was built on the basis of the giant
oil producer.
</P>
<P>
Daqing's 50-million-ton annual capacity will last until the
year 2010, he told an economic and technological cooperation fair
which is going on in south China's Hunan Province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
