<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Forest Shelter Project Helps Stop Advance of Sand Dunes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The forest shelter project in
north, northwest and northeast China that began in 1978 has had
some encouraging results.
</P>
<P>
In the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, which accounts for 10
million hectares, or one third of the designed hectareage for the
project, trees have been planted on 4 million hectares and another
one million hectares are being planted.
</P>
<P>
The project has helped improve natural conditions on more than
5 million hectares of arid land and stop soil erosion on 4 million
hectares of land at barren hillside, according to Gao Xilin,
deputy director of the region's forestry bureau.
</P>
<P>
The project has also protected over one million hectares of
farmland and more than 2 million hectares of pastures.
</P>
<P>
Gao says that the project's success has much to do with the
forestry research in the region. In the past decade, the region
has made 400 scientific research achievements, more than 40 percent
of which have been used for tree planting.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to be completed by the year 2050.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
