<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Host UNCTAD Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will host the 10th
international meeting of the United Nations Conference on Trade
and Development (UNCTAD) in the year 2000, according to the Thai
Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Hosting the U.N. development forum, which was agreed upon by
the Thai cabinet Tuesday, will enable Thailand to play a key role
in laying down the future principle of international economic
development strategies by taking into account the interest of
developing countries, Kitti Wasinondh, Foreign Ministry deputy
spokesman was quoted Wednesday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
In concrete terms, the UNCTAD's plan to establish an Institute
for Comparative Development in Thailand will increase Bangkok's
role in development fields, Kitti said.
</P>
<P>
It is also expected that Thailand will earn about 8.9 million
U.S. dollars from the spending of 3,000 participants from 188
members due to attend the forum, Kitti said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Commerce Minister Supachai
Panitchpakdi said recently that the UNCTAD's conference in the
next two years will be a "turning point" for Asia to show the rest
of the world that it has successfully recovered from the
recession.
</P>
<P>
Starting in Bangkok in July last year, the financial crisis
spread throughout the region, resulting in devaluation of regional
currencies, collapse of insolvent firms and massive unemployment.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD was established in 1964 and played a key role in
voicing the positions of developing countries in many
international trade negotiation forums.
</P>
<P>
The 10th UNCTAD meeting will bring together government leaders
as well as ministers. The ministerial meeting normally takes place
every four years with a rotation of host countries among Asia,
Africa and Latin America. 
</P>
