<HEADLINE> India Plans to Set Up Two "Toy Cities" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government plans
to set up two "toy cities" in a bid to expand its toy export base
in the world market, official sources said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two "cities," or new manufacturing zones, being established
in Navi Mumbai, 1,407 kilometers southwest of New Delhi, and
Greater Noida near New Delhi, will target buyers in the United
States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
"Our toy industry is poised for a major breakthrough in the
export market since we have the potential, capability and
entrepreneurship," said R. H. Naqvi, executive director of the
Electronics and Computer Software Export Promotion Council, which
has been designated by the Commerce Ministry to service the export
interests of toy manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
For the Navi Mumbai production zone, for instance, the Small
Scale Industries Development Corporation has allotted over 40
hectares. The complex would not be just an industrial center but
an integrated "city," complete with not only production units and
showrooms but also design centers, facilities to give
technological inputs and quality improvement and a toy museum.
</P>
<P>
Export of toys from India has been marginal but the growth has
been impressive of late, rising from 2.89 million U.S. dollars in
value in 1995-96 to 15 million dollars in 1996-97 and 16 million
dollars in 1997-98. 
</P>
