<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Up 44.7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus
in the first half of fiscal 1998 jumped 44.7 percent from the
previous year to 7,410.8 billion yen (about 53.9 billion
U.S. dollars), the Finance Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ministry officials attributed the increase to Japan's poor domestic
demand stemming from the recession and to robust demand for Japanese
goods in European and U.S. markets.
</P>
<P>
Overall exports increased 2.4 percent to 25,908.7 billion yen
(about 188.5 billion dollars) in the April-September period, the ninth
straight half-year of growth, while imports fell 8.3 percent to
18,497.8 billion yen (about 134.6 billion dollars), the second
straight half-yearly drop, the ministry said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
In the April-September period, Japan's politically sensitive
trade surplus with the United States increased 41.3 percent to
3,424.2 billion yen (about 24.9 billion dollars), extending its
winning streak to the fourth straight half-year term, boosted by
strong demand in the U.S. for Japanese vehicles and steel products.
</P>
<P>
Japan's trade surplus with other Asian nations tumbled 35.5 percent
to 2,104.1 billion yen (about 15.3 billion dollars), the first fall in
three half-year periods, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus with the 15-member European Union (EU) soared
88.1 percent to 2,197.0 billion yen (about 15.9 billion dollars),
marking the eighth straight gain for a half-year term.
</P>
<P>
Japan's merchandise trade balance is measured on the basis of goods
clearing customs and is reported before adjustment for seasonal
factors.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen averaged 137.47 to the U.S. dollar in the
reporting period, down 13.4 percent from the year-earlier level. A
weak yen lowers the price of Japanese products overseas and increases
the yen value of sales in foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
Japan's trade balance hinges on the yen's value against the dollar,
an economist at a private financial institution said.
</P>
<P>
"If the yen goes up further, imports will increase and the surplus
will begin to narrow. But if the correction of the weak yen comes to a
halt and the currency falls back, the trend will remain unchanged," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sino-Finnish Relations in Vigorous Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Finnish Prime Minister Paavo
Lipponen will start a five-day official visit to China next
Monday, widely expected to bring existing dynamic overall
Sino-Finnish friendship and cooperation into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Finland and China have maintained a sound and smooth
relationship in the last five decades, which saw the world in much
turmoil and rapid changes.
</P>
<P>
The 1990s marked a new phase in the Sino-Finnish friendship
with frequent exchanges of high-level visits between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
In July 1995, President Jiang Zemin made a landmark visit to
Finland as the first Chinese president visiting the Nordic
country. Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari returned the visit in
April 1996.
</P>
<P>
In September last year, just after the Communist Party of China
(CPC) concluded its 15th National Congress, the two presidents met
again as Ahtisaari made a stopover in Beijing on his way to
Japan. The Finnish president became the first foreign leader that
heard Jiang's briefing on the CPC National Congress.
</P>
<P>
The smooth progress of the Sino-Finnish political relations has
promoted an all-round development of bilateral ties in the fields
of economy and trade, science and technology as well as defense
and culture.
</P>
<P>
As far back as in 1953, China and Finland signed a governmental
trade and payment agreement -- the first between the People's
Republic of China and a Western country.
</P>
<P>
In the many years that followed, bilateral trade has been
growing steadily on the basis of mutual benefit and supplying each
other's needs.
</P>
<P>
Since the mid-1990s, with Finland's new strategy to explore the
Asian market, Sino-Finnish trade has been increasing at a high
rate averaging 20 percent annually, easily meeting the target of
doubling bilateral trade volume within three years, as set by the
two presidents.
</P>
<P>
Finland, with a population of 5.1 million, is a world leader in
forest industry, paper machinery, telecommunications,
environmental protection and biological technology. Sino-Finnish
cooperation in science and technology has been an important
driving force in the bilateral economic and trade relations.
</P>
<P>
Significant achievements in combining technology with trade
included Sino-Finnish joint projects of transporting water from
the suburban Miyun reservoir to Beijing in the winter season,
preventing floods in the lower reaches of the Yellow River caused
by melted ice and fur processing in Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996, the two countries had signed 96 contracts
importing Finnish technology into China with a total value of 656
million U.S. dollars, in areas including nonferrous metallurgy,
paper making and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, the two countries signed an agreement to
build a Sino-Finnish science and technology park to strengthen
their cooperation in personnel training, business management and
supporting enterprise development.
</P>
<P>
Active financial cooperation has provided a key channel for the
rapid development of bilateral economic and trade relations. The
Finnish government started to give China mixed loans as early as
in the mid-1980s when the two countries reached credit agreement.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, loan agreements were signed on 66
contracts with a total of 370 million dollars in government
preferential loans from Finland, for projects including paper
making, wood processing, urban heating, energy, communication and
health care.
</P>
<P>
Finland established its first joint venture in China in 1984
and has since set up more than 70 such ventures, with investment
of 280 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Prestigious Finnish companies including Nokia have their
manufacture and research bases in China aimed at long-term
development as the Chinese market has provided huge opportunities
for Finnish enterprises.
</P>
<P>
In the defense sector, contacts between military leaders of the
two countries have also markedly increased in the past years.
</P>
<P>
In the cultural sector, exchanges between the two countries
have been flourishing in the last few years, contributing to the
mutual understanding and friendship between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
It is widely agreed that Finland and China are expecting an
even brighter future with the coming of the 21st century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
