<HEADLINE> Microsoft Reports Record Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft Corp., the
world's largest software-maker, Tuesday reported a 153 percent
rise in its first-quarter operating earnings, compared the same
period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
News release from the company said the software giant earned
1.68 billion U.S. dollars in the quarter ended on September 30, up
from 663 million dollars in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Revenue rose 26 percent to 3.95 billion dollars from 3.13
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft admitted that the results for the just-ended quarter
reflected a one-time gain of 160 million dollars from the sale of
the software subsidiary SoftImage as well as a write-off of 296
million dollars related to the purchase of WebTV networks.
</P>
<P>
Excluding one-time items, Microsoft said it earned 1.52 billion
dollars in the first quarter, up 58 percent from 959 million
dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
"It was a terrific quarter," said analyst Rick Sherlund of
Goldman Sachs in New York, "the margins are at record levels and
they gave very bullish guidance going forward."
</P>
<P>
Microsoft attributed its record earnings to surprisingly strong
overseas demand for its new Windows 98 operating system, launched
on June 25.
</P>
<P>
The company said it has sold 10 million copies of Windows 98,
either as retail packages or with new computers. The demand for
Windows 98 was stronger than expected in several European
countries and Japan, although the overall outlook for Asia remains
"tepid," according to the news release.
</P>
<P>
Analysts noted the earnings were posted as Microsoft's lawyers
defended it in a federal court in Washington D.C., against the
government's landmark antitrust lawsuit against the software giant.
</P>
<P>
The government contends Microsoft used its influence as the
maker of Windows to try to dominate other software markets.
Microsoft says that while it played hard against competitors, it
played fair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
