<HEADLINE> Over 5,000 Sri Lankan Deserters Surrender Under Amnesty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 21 (Xinhua) -- During a three-day amnesty
offered to military deserters which ended Monday night in Sri
Lanka, 5,112 deserters surrendered to the authorities, local
newspaper the Island reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Following appeals by the parents of a number of deserters, the
Defense Ministry announced the amnesty effective from 8:00 a.m.
Saturday to Monday night which the ministry said would be the
final one to be granted to deserters.
</P>
<P>
The deserters who surrender during the amnesty period would be
re-trained, re-equipped and sent to their respective regiments.
Their salaries and allowances would be paid from the date of
rejoining the service, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
The deserters were being recalled as an alternative to
conscription to strengthen the army in the wake of the on-going
war in the north and east of the country against the Tamil rebels
who have been fighting for 15 years for a separate state.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated the number of deserters was near 25,000 by May
this year. Since 1995, the army has offered amnesty to deserters
on several occasions, and more than 14,500 of them had returned
for their duty.
</P>
<P>
The police and army Tuesday began a search operation to arrest
the other deserters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
