<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Ask EU for Three-Year GSP Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will formally ask the
European Union (EU) to maintain preferential tariffs for it on
three key agricultural exports for three more years instead of
ending them as scheduled on January 1.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Commerce Ministry and Foreign Ministry will jointly
make the request for the grace period to the European Commission,
according to the Thai Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Under the Generalized System of Preference (GSP), developing
countries are allowed to export certain products to the EU at
lower tariffs in order to help them build markets abroad.
</P>
<P>
The EU has been gradually raising tariffs on several categories
of Thai goods, which used to enjoy more favorable rates. The GSP
protection for Thailand will end completely on January 1.
</P>
<P>
Next year, fresh shrimp will be taxed at 14.4 percent, compared
with 9.7 percent currently, and 4.5 percent before 1997. Boiled
shrimp will be taxed at 20 percent, compared with 13.5 percent now
and 6 percent before 1997.
</P>
<P>
The EU will raise tariffs on Thai fresh fruit next year to 10.6
percent, compared with 9 percent currently, and 6 percent in the
years before 1997.
</P>
<P>
The tariffs on fresh flowers, now 20.4 percent, will rise to 22
percent from 15 percent before 1997. Processed pineapple will face
tariffs ranging from 21.3 percent to 25.1 percent, compared with
19.7 percent to 23.2 percent currently, and 12-15 percent prior to
1997.
</P>
<P>
Pisanu Rienmahasarn, deputy director-general of the Foreign
Trade Department of the Thai Commerce Ministry, was quoted
Wednesday by the Bangkok Post as saying that Thailand had a chance
if the Europeans could be made to understand how much the economy
had slumped in the past year.
</P>
<P>
He said the EU decided to terminate GSP rates for Thailand
based on earlier economic growth indicators. Per capita annual
income in one figure used to determine whether a country should be
"graduated" from the program, and the method of calculating the
figure has been disputed.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income of Thailand is expected to fall this year by
7 percent, from about 2,000 U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Somsak Paneetatyasai, vice-president of the Thai Frozen Foods
Association, said Shrimp exports to the EU would be severely
affected if the GSP was removed.
</P>
<P>
Thai shrimp exports to the EU over the first seven months of
this year rose year-on-year by 27.35 percent to 9,302 tons, with
the value rising by 123.98 percent to 3.8 billion baht (95 million
U.S. dollars), Somsak said. This was mainly because the EU had
banned shrimp imports from India and Pakistan for several months
on sanitary grounds.
</P>
<P>
The EU is Thailand's fourth largest shrimp export market. Last
year, it imported 12,993 tons of Thai shrimp worth 3.7 billion
Baht (92.5 million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
