<HEADLINE> Internet Pioneer Jonathan Postel Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Jonathan Postel, an
Internet pioneer, died at the age of 55 in a Los Angeles hospital
over the weekend following a heart surgery, his friends and
colleagues said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Postel, who was often called "the father of the Internet,"
began his work linking computers in the 1960s when he was a
graduate student at the University of California in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
He was director of the controversial Internet Assigned Numbers
Authority, which assigns Internet addresses throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
He remained active in Internet policy matters until his
hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
On October 2, he presented what he called a consensus solution
from the Internet community to the Clinton administration -- a
plan to put management of the addressing system into the hands of
a private non-profit group.
</P>
<P>
"Jon Postel was an important historical figure in the
development of the Internet," one of his colleagues, Network
Solutions Inc. Chief Executive Officer Gabe Battista, said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
He said Postel's work over the past decades "played a
significant part in the worldwide growth and development of the
Internet as we know it today." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Passes 520 Billion Dollar Spending Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives Tuesday approved a 520 billion U.S. dollar
spending bill offering cash to farmers, teachers and the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
The 333-95 vote reflected a compromise, reached last week
between the White House and congressional leaders, that gave both
parties victories to brag about.
</P>
<P>
It also indicated that most lawmakers were weary of the 1998
budget fight and eager to go home to take part in the campaign for
the November 3 congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
Republicans could claim their victories such as blocking
President Clinton's plans for voluntary national student testing,
boosting spending against illegal drugs and winning more than 8
billion dollars for military readiness and other Pentagon programs.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Democrats talked of money they won to let
communities begin hiring 100,000 teachers, help poor families pay
heating bills, provide summer jobs for youths and clean up toxic
wastes.
</P>
<P>
Still, large numbers of both Republicans and Democrats were
voting for the measure. That phenomenon stood in contrast to a
year that saw the two parties square off repeatedly over budget
priorities, health care, campaign finance law, tobacco regulation
and Clinton's possible impeachment.
</P>
<P>
The legislation covers almost a third of the 1.7 trillion
dollar federal budget for fiscal 1999, which started from October
1. It is an amalgam of eight of the 13 spending bills for the
year that were overdue because of disputes between the two parties
and within the GOP itself.
</P>
<P>
The over-4,000-page-long bill also includes providing 18
billion dollars for the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and
putting a three-year moratorium on new taxes on Internet
commerce. It would prepare government computers for the year 2000
and help 40,000 Haitian immigrants become permanent U.S. residents.
</P>
<P>
The House Speaker Newt Gingrich defended the legislation
against accusations by some conservatives that it represented a
retreat from Republican goals of cutting taxes and spending.
</P>
</TEXT>
