<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwatch Hopes Climate Change Conference Makes Difference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S.-based Worldwatch
Institute Tuesday hoped the coming conference on climate change in
Brazil can dissolve the obstacles hindering reduction of the green
house gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
Three sticking questions unresolved would be faced by the
negotiators in the fourth conference of the parties to the Climate
Change Treaty next month in Buenos Aires, said Christopher Flavin,
vice president of Worldwatch Institute in Washington.
</P>
<P>
These questions include developing countries' role in slowing
the pace of world-wide unfavorable climate change, the so called
"Carbon Sinks" for the developed nations and the Emissions Trading
issues.
</P>
<P>
Flavin said that the opinion gap between the United States and
the developing world appears to be widening since the last
Conference.
</P>
<P>
The United States said it would not ratify the Kyoto Protocol
passed at the last conference without "scheduled commitments to
limit or reduce emissions" by developing countries. However most
developing countries' per capita emissions are less than one-tenth
of the U.S.'s level. Most developing countries therefore opposed
to adopt early emission limits, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the "carbon sinks" issue, said Flavin, the Kyoto Protocol
provides that industrial countries have the option to offset their
greenhouse gas emissions by taking the greenhouse gas absorbed by
their forests into account. But the Worldwatch thinks there is no
scientific ground to provide such an option.
</P>
<P>
Emissions trading is a potentially effective means of ensuring
the cost-effectiveness of emissions reduction investments. But
this concept might also be undermined by the unnecessarily
generous emissions reduction allowances provided by the United
States to Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. plan to pay Russia tens of billions of U.S. dollars as
"hot air" emissions allowance is under extensive criticism by many
environmental protection organizations including the Greenpeace.
</P>
<P>
Conditions are ripe now for the governments and industrial
sector to take the leadership in making more ambitious plans to
slow the unfavorable change of the world climate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
