<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Professor Sees Bright Prospects for Human Rights in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Human rights in China have
bright prospects, said Swiss Professor Norbert Meienberger from
Zurich University, who is here to take part in the on-going
International Symposium on Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
Meienberger, a renown Sinologist in Switzerland, has visited
China for several times since 1970s.
</P>
<P>
In a interview with Xinhua, he expressed his opinion about the
differences between Chinese and Western conceptions of human
rights.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the Western conception, the Chinese conception
is much more comprehensive as it is not limited to the classic
political and civil rights, he said.
</P>
<P>
"China emphasizes more on the rights to subsist and to
develop," Meienberger added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the differences are caused by different
historical, economic and cultural background in China and Western
countries.
</P>
<P>
According to him, one of the main reasons that hinter the
development of human rights in China is the legacy of China's long
feudal history that still haunts its present.
</P>
<P>
"Feudalism was certainly no hotbed for human rights", he
claimed.
</P>
<P>
He said that the 20th century was in China "a time of
revolution and armed resistance" and it was not the period to be
preoccupied with human rights.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Cultural Revolution "was devastating China"
just at a time when orderly and lawful government was needed even
more than before. Even today, neglecting the law still occurs
frequently in China.
</P>
<P>
"Under such conditions, do human rights in China have bright
prospects? The answer is yes." said the Swiss Sinologist.
</P>
<P>
"As great changes have taken place, the policy of reforms and
opening up has helped improve the living condition of the Chinese
people in the past twenty years to such an extent. I am convinced
that the Chinese government will continue the policy of reform and
opening," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that "the forces accusing China" mainly consist
of three groupings. The first is "anti-communist elements who are
interested in continuing the cold war". They are not necessarily
interested in human rights, but they welcome criticism along these
lines "because it adds fuel to their cause".
</P>
<P>
The second, he said, is made up of people who believe only the
West has correct conception of human rights. They assume that
China should adopt the Western conception, including Western
democracy, as a prerequisite to be able to observe human rights.
</P>
<P>
It reflects sort of cultural imperialist thinking, Meienberger
noted.
</P>
<P>
A third group of critics comprises mainly civil servants and
scholars who see that the situation in China is not ideal and wish
to discuss ways and means with the Chinese side for the betterment
of the application of human rights in the country.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that criticism of the human rights situation in
China "deeply roots in anti-communism and cultural imperialism and
reflects only in part genuine concern of foreigners for an
improvement of the situation in China".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Continues to Increase in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Overseas investors injected
more than two billion U.S. dollars of capital in real terms into
businesses in the Chinese capital Beijing during the first three
quarters of this year, an increase of 18.6 percent on a yearly
basis.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the Beijing Municipal Committee of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation say that the city approved 503 foreign-funded
enterprises in the nine months, with contracted foreign investment
involved grew 29.4 percent year on year to 3.19 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The growth momentum is attributed to the increase of foreign
direct investment, which grew 20.4 percent year on year to 1.41
billion U.S. dollars in the nine months to September.
</P>
<P>
Over 54 percent, or 770 million U.S. dollars, of the foreign
direct investment was put into the real estate industry, which
remained the focus of foreign investment in the city.
</P>
<P>
The increased foreign investment is also attributed to
increases by well-known multinationals, which funded over 30
projects in Beijing, with combined investment reaching 950 million
U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
