<HEADLINE> Dollar Value of Thai Export Products Slips </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The dollar value of Thailand's
export products in several key sectors, especially farm and
agro-industrial goods, declined by 15 percent in the first eight
months of this year despite an increase in volume of 11.5 percent,
according to a report issued by the Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Proceeds from rice exports fell year-on-year by 20 percent to
1.39 billion U.S. dollars, though the export volume rose by 34.7
percent over the 4.3 million tons recorded in the first eight
months of last year.
</P>
<P>
The value of frozen and processed chicken exports fell by 20.5
percent and that of rubber by 36.8 percent, while the export
volumes increased by 46.4 percent and 10.6 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Hard bargaining by importers was partially responsible for the
decline in value, said the report available Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from exports of integrated circuits totaled 1.47
billion dollars (down 12.6 percent), gems and jewelry 888 million
dollars (down 23.2 percent), shoes and accessories 613 million
dollars (down 21 percent), and plastic pellets and products 470
million dollars (down 14.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the regional economic crisis had reduced
the purchasing power in Asian markets, while the financial crisis
in Russia had weakened imports from Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Official export figures for the first eight months of the year
showed a decline in dollar value by 5.2 percent to 35.96 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports also dropped substantially, resulting in a trade
surplus of 7.4 billion U.S. dollars for the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
