<HEADLINE> Sihanouk to Leave Phnom Penh in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's King Norodom
Sihanouk is planning to leave Phnom Penh for Beijing on November
11, the Cambodia Daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a faxed message to the Cambodia Daily, King Sihanouk said he
would leave Cambodia round November 11.
</P>
<P>
The King had already delayed his trip to Beijing for medical
treatment after senior government officials urged him to stay
until a coalition government is formed.
</P>
<P>
The King, who came here on October 5, last came to Phnom Penh
on December 3, 1997, and stayed until Jan 5 when he abruptly left
the capital for Beijing. He has been at his royal residence in
Siem Reap since April 11.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that the King's stay in the country will
ease tensions between the two rival parties, one of them is led by
Second Prime Minister Hun Sen and other headed by Prince Ranariddh
and Sam Rainsy.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said King Sihanouk is respected by all sides and is in
a position to help end the current political deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Once the King leaves, Cambodia will be without a legal head of
state unless the National Assembly meets and chooses a president.
</P>
<P>
FUNCINPEC and the Sam Rainsy Party have urged the King to hold
a summit in Beijing instead of Phnom Penh, where opposition
leaders have said they might not be safe.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Cambodian People's Party (CPP) and Second Prime
Minister Hun Sen have opposed talks outside Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
But CPP spokesman Khieu Kanharith said the ruling party would
not refuse a direct request from the monarch if he decided to call
a summit in Beijing after leaving.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the spokesman said his party would love to have a
coalition agreement before the King's departure. "For us, the
sooner, the better, but we have to wait for those on the outside
to come back." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
