<HEADLINE> Brazil, IMF Close to 30 Billion Dollar Bailout Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRAZILIA, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Brazil and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) Tuesday were near to an agreement on a 30
billion U.S. dollar bailout package.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, Inter-American Development Bank and other
private banks are expected to fund the bailout package, according
to a joint statement issued on Tuesday by Brazil and the IMF.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is reportedly the latest victim of the financial crisis
started in Asia last year. Brazil has lost 25 billion dollars in
foreign exchange reserves since August this year, when Russia's
debt default caused new investment crises in many emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts fear that instability in Brazil may develop into
an overall economic crisis in the whole Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The Brazil-IMF statement said the two sides held talks this
weekend to prepare "the ground for prompt support from the
international community, including the IMF, for the multi-year
fiscal program to be announced soon by the Brazilian government,
which will include new policy initiatives" in dealing with the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will continue their talks to reach a formal
agreement, the statement announced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
