<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Urged to Open Domestic Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Participants in an Italy-Japan
Business Group meeting Tuesday urged Japan to get rid of
protectionism and open its domestic market if it wants to overcome
its current economic and financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 10th assembly of the group held here Tuesday,
World Trade Organization (WTO) Director General Renato Ruggiero,
an Italian, observed that protectionism "could turn out to be a
tragic mistake. No nation today can afford to build walls against
investment."
</P>
<P>
On ties between Italy and Japan, Ruggiero said their "relations
have improved, but they have not yet reached their potential."
</P>
<P>
He added that the effects of the crisis in Japan are beginning
to be felt here. In the first eight months of the year, Italy's
exports to Japan dropped 8 percent, while the imports went up 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
Ruggiero's viewpoints were echoed by some Italian senior
officials and businessmen participating in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Trade Minister Augusto Fantozzi said that in
order to resolve Japan's problems, fiscal measures alone are not
enough and the best way is to open its domestic market to foreign
goods and services.
</P>
<P>
Fantozzi went on to say that Italy has good prospects to
attract foreign investment, in particular from Japan.
</P>
<P>
The need to bolster cooperation between Italy, a member nation
of the European Union, and Japan was stressed by Italian Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini, who said that this would help ensure the
success of the process of opening and liberalizing markets.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation, Dini said, must also and above all aim at
avoiding any temptation of protectionism, which he described as a
step backward that can only pave the way for new economic, social
and political conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 government officials, businessmen, economists from
both Italy and Japan took part in the annual meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0245 </DOCNO>
