<HEADLINE> More Brazilians Study in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, October 20 (Xinhua) -- The number of Brazilians
studying in British schools has gone up by 153 percent between
1994 and 1997, the local press reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian newspaper "Estado de Sao Paulo" said that 16,200
Brazilians studied in British schools in 1997, againts 6,400
people in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper said that since 1994, more Brazilians have
decided to invest in studies in foreign schools, especially in the
United States which has five times more Brazilian students than
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 85 percent of Brazilians take English classes while 15
percent follow graduate and post-graduate courses.
</P>
<P>
The studies preferred by Brazilian students are business
management, followed by medicine, computer sciences, design,
journalism and social sciences. 
</P>
