<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Platinum, Diamond Jewelry Popular In Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Platinum and diamonds are
replacing gold and jadeite as the favorite ornament of the people
of Shanghai, according to sources at a recent gem and jade fair.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the fair showed 578 million yuan in sales of
platinum and diamond jewelry in the city last year in the city.
</P>
<P>
The jewelry shops of Shanghai now have special counters for
platinum and diamond jewelry and at least 90 shops are mainly
engaged in the processing and sale of platinum and diamond
jewelry. This is in marked contrast to five years ago, when there
were only a few shops in the trade.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is the country's leading gold jewelry market and has
sold more than 130 tons of gold jewelry since it was allowed to
get into the business in 1982. But it sold only 4.25 tons of gold
jewelry from January to June this year, a drop of 12.6 percent
from the same period last year and the lowest period in the four
years. In 1993, it sold a record 22 tons of gold jewelry.
</P>
<P>
The number of gold jewelry shops has decreased from 380 in 1994
to 250 at present. To attract more customers, many of them have
started since 1993 a "changing new with the old" method, whereby a
customer can get new jewelry by paying to exchange or rework old
jewelry.
</P>
<P>
Shrinking gold jewelry sales are largely blamed on gold's loss
of popularity as an investment while increased platinum and
diamond sales are attributed to international consumer trends and
the quality guarantees of platinum and diamond jewelry.
</P>
<P>
The world's diamond giant De Beers predicted that by the year
2000, China's diamond jewelry sales will exceed 20 billion yuan,
and that the country will become the world's third largest diamond
market, after the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
De Beers put China's diamond jewelry sales at 3.75 billion yuan
last year, a rise of 13.6 percent over 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Texas Floods Force Thousands Homeless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS AGNELES, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of people in the
U.S. state of Texas fled from their homes Tuesday as devastating
floods destroyed farmland and houses and claimed 20 lives, local
officials reported.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rain, caused by humid air streaming off two hurricanes in
the Pacific Ocean off the west coast of Mexico, has caused floods
in about 60 of the 254 counties in Texas.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities have confirmed 20 deaths related to the
floods and Governor George W. Bush asked President Clinton to
declare 20 counties disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
The torrential rainfall, which has soaked the area since the
weekend, appeared to be easing, but swollen rivers flooded cities
as the waters raced downstream.
</P>
<P>
In Cuero, a town of 7,000 some 90 miles (145 kilometers)
southeast of San Antonio, floods heavily hit the business areas
and destroyed one-fourth of houses, said local officials.
</P>
<P>
In Caldwell County, northeast of San Antonio, up to 5,000
cattle were roaming free -- set loose when the flooded San Marcos
River washed away pens, barns and hundreds of miles of fencing.
</P>
<P>
Helicopters from the Coast Guard and the Texas Department of
Public Safety were helping with the evacuation effort, picking up
stranded residents from their rooftops.
</P>
<P>
Insured losses related to the storms were expected to exceed 90
million U.S. dollar, the Southwestern Insurance Information
Service estimated Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"These could be the most costly flood losses for insurers in
decades," said spokesman Jerry Johns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
