<HEADLINE> Ecuador Seeks Support for Border Dispute With Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Ecuadoran President Jamil Mahuad
left for Argentina and Chile Tuesday to seek support in a
long-running border dispute with Peru.
</P>
<P>
Mahuad said he would seek the support of Presidents Carlos
Menem of Argentina and Eduardo Frei of Chile for his country's
claim on the border dispute.
</P>
<P>
Peru's Foreign Minister Fernando de Trazegnies said in Lima on
the same day that Mahuad's trip would not reverse a decision
reportedly made by the four mediating countries that Peru has the
sovereignty over the border area in dispute.
</P>
<P>
The mediating group is made up of Brazil, the United States,
Chile and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Both Ecuador and Peru claim the Andean region of Tiwintza,
which extends over 49 miles (79 kilometers) of unmarked border in
a remote stretch of mountainous jungle.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have fought three wars in 1941, 1981 and
1995 over the disputed area.
</P>
<P>
In 1942, the two countries signed the Rio de Janeiro agreement
to settle the border dispute. The pact, however, has never been
accepted by Ecuador. 
</P>
</TEXT>
