<HEADLINE> State Assets Increase Sharply in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Assets of state-owned
enterprises in Shenzhen, one of China's four special economic
zones, have become 960 times greater than 18 years ago, going from
161 million yuan to 155.76 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
These companies led the country in reaching economic goals in
returns on investment and profits.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has 79 top-tier state enterprises, 1,114 second-level,
and 8,000 jointly run with other provinces. They have played an
increasingly important role in economic development, a local
government official said.
</P>
<P>
The amount of taxes paid by state-owned enterprises last year
accounted for 51 percent of the city's total, compared with 14.7
percent in 1981.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the success to reforms of state-owned
companies, the introduction of a modern enterprise system, and the
issue stocks within enterprise staff.  
</P>
</TEXT>
