<HEADLINE> Three South China Tigers Sent to Fujian Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, October 21 (Xinhua) -- Three South China Tiger cubs
have been sent from the Suzhou Zoo in east China's Jiangsu
Province to the Meihuashan Nature Reserve in the city of Longyan
in Fujian Province about 800 km southward.
</P>
<P>
The three cubs are the first tame tigers at a newly built South
China Tiger breeding center in the reserve, which is a natural
habitat for South China tigers, one of the most endangered animal
species in the world. It has a dozen wild South China Tigers.
</P>
<P>
When the three new tame tigers get old enough to have about a
dozen offspring in the 4-hectare center, they are expected to mate
with wild tigers to produce more South China Tigers.
</P>
<P>
The local government has spent 1.5 million yuan on the center
and will expand its area to 67 hectares.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
