<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Reports Death Toll of AIDS-Related Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA, October 20 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1,031 people have
died since 1984 from the Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome
(AIDS), a health ministry report said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 1,754 AIDS cases have been reported over
the past 14 years since the first case of AIDS was registered in
1984. Panama's population totals 2 million people.
</P>
<P>
Men made up 826 of the deaths, compared with only 205 women,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the victims were aged 20 to 44.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the majority of the victims had acquired
the disease through sexual contacts. It said that 858
HIV-positive patients were infected through heterosexual
relations, 451 through homosexual relations and 143 through
bisexual relations.
</P>
<P>
United Nations experts calculated that this year the number of
AIDS victims will total 30 million people worldwide, with
one-third of them to be youths aged 10 to 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
