<HEADLINE> Italy's New Government Will Not Change European Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Italy's new government will pursue
the European policy carried out by the outgoing central-left
administration led by Romano Prodi, Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The European policy the Italian government has helped achieved
was used as an instrument to cope with the crisis sweeping the
financial market, Dini told the Italy-Japan Business Group session.
</P>
<P>
He added that the new government led by Massimo D'Alema of the
Left Democrat Party will provide a "strong signal" to the European
Union by strengthening the "government of the economy."
</P>
<P>
He said the European countries, Japan and the United States
should jointly push forward the international financial reform to
ensure the free movement of capital and the stability of the
financial system.
</P>
<P>
Dini now serves as the foreign minister of a care-taker
cabinet. Prod's government lost the confidence vote at the house
of deputies on October 9 and resigned. President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro has asked D'Alema to form a new government. 
