<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection Benefits in Southeastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANTOU, October 21 (Xinhua) -- The coastal city of Shantou in
Guangdong Province has spent 9.75 million yuan (about 1.2 million
U.S. dollars) on 70 environmental protection projects that have
made the city both beautiful and attractive to foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The projects have increased the city's waste gas treatment
capacity by 67,300 standard cubic meters per hour and waste water
treatment capacity by 7,211 tons per day.
</P>
<P>
The city government has passed a series of laws and regulations
on environmental protection since 1994 that require a license to
discharge waste materials. In March it issued licenses to the
first batch of about 1,000 work units.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two dust-control zones have been set up in an
87.5-square kilometer area, improving the city's air quality.
</P>
<P>
Vehicles were not allowed to use their horns in urban areas as
of June last year, and construction sites are inspected frequently
to check on noise pollution.
</P>
<P>
The city also spent more than two million yuan on a green belt
around Longhugou, a river running across the city, and special
attention has been paid to protecting the Hanjiang, the city's
main drinking water source.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
