<HEADLINE> NBA Players' Union Considering Decertification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- After losing its guaranteed
contracts in a ruling by an arbitrator, the NBA players' union
spent Tuesday pondering its latest loss and remained upbeat.
</P>
<P>
Union director Billy Hunter said: "The players will not back do
 wn. The sooner the owners realize this and end the lockout, the
quicker we can avoid enormous damage to the sport of basketball."
</P>
<P>
Some agents were pushing for decertification, a move that
could lead to a multi-year fight with the owners.
</P>
<P>
By decertifying, the union would remove itself as the official
bargaining agent for the players. A court injunction would be
sought to end the lockout.
</P>
<P>
If an injunction were granted, the owners would lift the
lockout, open camps and impose new work rules. If the new rules
were more restrictive than the old ones, the players would be
expected to file an antitrust suit against the league seeking
damages.
</P>
<P>
The agents' advisory council meets in Las Vegas on Wednesday.
Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen and Karl Malone are among those
expected to attend a union meeting open to all players on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
NBA players who currently have long-term contracts might
benefit from decertification, but free agents would be hurt.
</P>
<P>
NBA Commissioner David Stern said: "Unfair labor practice
charges, arbitration, decertification, antitrust suits don't get
it done. This ruling should have been a signal that we return to
the table today." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
