<HEADLINE> Castro: Agents Sent to U.S. for Terrorism Against Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Cuban President Fidel Castro
said in a U.S. TV interview on Tuesday that the agents Cuba sent
to the U.S. were used to gather information about terrorist
activities against the Caribbean country.
</P>
<P>
In an interview aired by the Cable News Network (CNN), Castro
denied the agents are spying on the U.S. military.
</P>
<P>
"Yes, we have sometimes dispatched Cuban citizens to the United
States to infiltrate counter-revolutionary organizations, to
inform us about activities that are of great interest to us,"
Castro said.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have the right to do this... The United States has
spies in industrial quantities."
</P>
<P>
FBI agents last month rounded up 10 people in south Florida
accused of spying for the government in Havana.
</P>
<P>
"What information in the United States is it that interests
us? One bit of information exclusively -- one thing fundamentally
-- and that is the information about the terrorist activities
against Cuba. The information about sabotage plans," Castro said.
</P>
<P>
Cuba was not interested in "strategic matters, nor are we
interested in information about military bases," he said in
Spanish with an English interpretation.
</P>
<P>
He added that U.S. military movements in areas near Cuba would
be of interest if they "translate into an act of aggression
against Cuba. But we know that at this time that is not the
fundamental thinking of the U.S. government." 
</P>
</TEXT>
