<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Official Praises 1999 Women's World Cup Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- A FIFA's official declared
the Jack Kent Cooke Stadium is among the world's finest soccer
fields.
</P>
<P>
The stadium will be the site of six matches during the 1999
Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Per Ravn Omdal, the chairman of FIFA's organizing committee
for women's soccer, said the new stadium is even a better soccer
site than RFK Stadium, which held games during the 1994 men's
World Cup and is regarded by many world soccer officials as an
ideal facility.
</P>
<P>
Cooke Stadium is "just splendid," said Omdal, a Norwegian who
also is vice president of UEFA, Europe's soccer governing body.
</P>
<P>
Cooke Stadium, opened last year with 80,000 seats, will be the
site of four first-round games and two quarterfinal matches.
</P>
<P>
Omdal and members of the Women's World Cup organizing
committee are in the process of touring all eight of the stadiums
that will be used for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen teams will participate in the tournament, which will
involve 32 matches played as 17 events from June 19 to July 10.
All matches will be staged as doubleheaders except the
semifinals, which will be played in Foxboro, Massachusetts, and
Palo Alto, California.
</P>
<P>
More than 150,000 tickets have been sold for the tournament, a
figure that already exceeds the total of 112,000 tickets sold for
the 1995 World Cup in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Marla Messing, the Women's World Cup Organizing Committee
president, said the committee will break even if it sells 400,000
tickets (about 24,500 in attendance per match).
</P>
<P>
"Even with an event as large as the Olympics, the awareness
doesn't really come until very, very close to the event, and
that's when you sell most of the tickets," Messing said. "For us
to have sold 150,000 is really incredible."
</P>
<P>
Messing said capacity crowds are the goal for the opening
match on June 19 at Giants Stadium, the semifinals, the final and
games in which the United States is involved.
</P>
<P>
For other matches, however, Messing said, the goal is crowds
of 15,000 to 20,000.
</P>
<P>
All 32 matches will be nationally televised on ABC, ESPN or
ESPN2. The draw for the tournament will be held at the weekend of
February 13-14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
