the Nevada Athletic Commission, saying he would teach Tyson how
to handle his money and his career.
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully, I'll handle all of that for him, choose the right
team for him," Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
Finkel wants Tyson to fight on December 5 in Las Vegas. But
Don King, Tyson's former promoter, still holds contracts binding
Tyson to fight for him. Tyson has sued King to get out of the
contracts, but the case is far from being decided.
</P>
<P>
Tyson's advisers have been working on King in hopes of
reaching a settlement that will allow Tyson to use another
promoter. King said Monday he is happy for Tyson to get his
license back.
</P>
<P>
"I am delighted Tyson will be able to fight again," said King,
whom Tyson has accused of stealing millions of dollars from him.
</P>
<P>
Tyson owes the Internal Revenue Service 13 million U.S.
dollars in back taxes, and is nearly broke despite having made
100 million dollars in purses in his last six fights.
</P>
<P>
"I have no more financial problems now," Tyson said after the
hearing. 
