<HEADLINE> Griffith Joyner Inducted into Hall of Fame </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Florence Griffith Joyner,
who died last month at age of 38, was inducted into the Hall of
Fame Monday, according to a press report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Griffith Joyner, who set the women's world records in the 100 m
eters and 200 meters and won three gold medals at the Seoul
Olympics in 1988, died suddenly during her sleep. The reason of
death is yet to know.
</P>
<P>
Al Joyner, Griffith Joyner's husband, wasn't the only person
in tears as he accepted on behalf of his wife.
</P>
<P>
Joyner said his wife didn't care about being known as the
world's fastest woman. "She wanted to be known as a wife, a
mother and a motivator of children."
</P>
<P>
There was also a tribute at the ceremony to two-time Olympic
gold medalist Jackie Joyner-Kersee, who retired from competition
this summer. Joyner-Kersee is the late Griffith Joyner's
sister-in-law.
</P>
<P>
Michael Jordan, an Olympic teammate in 1984, praised the track
and field superstar in a video presentation.
</P>
<P>
"We've come a long way since 1984. You, for women, have done a
heck of a job."
</P>
<P>
At the end of video, Jordan joked: "I don't think I can outrun
you. And I don't think you can outplay me."
</P>
<P>
Joyner-Kersee was a brilliant basketball player for her
university team. Olympic basketball gold medalist Dawn Staley
began the tribute to Joyner-Kersee. "I'm here to tell her she is
my hero," she said.
</P>
<P>
Joyner-Kersee, moved by the shower of praise, said she
appreciated the show of affection during this difficult time for
her family.
</P>
<P>
"This is an honor. My heart goes out to the Women's Sports
Foundation," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
