<HEADLINE> Tyson Ex-Manager File Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- The former co-manager of
Mike Tyson has filed suit against the boxer's new adviser Shelly
Finkel, seeking a 10 percent share in any money Tyson makes from
his next five fights.
</P>
<P>
The lawsuit was filed Tuesday in a district court in Las
Vegas, a day following Nevada State Athletic Commission gave back
Tyson license.
</P>
<P>
John K. Horne filed the lawsuit and named Finkel as defendant.
It claims interference with contractual relations between Tyson
and Horne.
</P>
<P>
"I'm not aware of it," Finkel said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Horne, who is now a movie producer in California, said in a
statement he believes he is entitled to a multimillion-dollar
award.
</P>
<P>
Tyson broke from Horne, Rory Hollowway and Don King in March,
filing lawsuits against each. He accused King of cheating, and
his co-managers of betraying him by arranging a deal that made
King the former champion's exclusive promoter. 
</P>
