<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Azerbaijan Elections Disappointing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
expressed disappointment Tuesday with what it said were
irregularities in the election process in Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular briefing at the Wye Plantation in
Maryland, Stated Department spokesman James Rubin said it was
hopeful for improvements in the 1999 municipal elections.
</P>
<P>
Rubin regretted that disagreements prevented agreement on the
composition of election commissions, which led several parties to
boycott the elections.
</P>
<P>
"Election day itself was marred by numerous and serious voting
irregularities, including ballot stuffing, problems with the vote
count and some inappropriate conduct by the election commissions,"
Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed particular concern over restrictions on the access
of Organization of Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE)
monitors to the vote counting process.
</P>
<P>
Azerbaijan rejected the interference of its domestic affairs by
the OSCE. President Heydar Aliyev won the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
