<HEADLINE> U.S. Concerned About Extremists in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
expressed grave concern Tuesday about reports that Rwandan Hutu
extremists are now actively involved in the Congo civil war.
</P>
<P>
"We condemn the Congolese government's efforts to recruit and
train these groups and view with alarm the fact that this conflict
is strengthening the hand of the perpetrators of the 1994 Rwandan
genocide, " State Department spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin made the remarks at a regular briefing in the Wye
Plantation, Maryland, where the Middle East summit is being
convened.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman urged all sides to halt further offensive action
and pursue immediate negotiations to resolve the underlying causes
of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Rebels opposed to President Laurent Kabila's government have
been making steady gains in eastern Congo since they took up arms
on August 2. Kabila has refused to negotiate with the rebels,
accusing them of being the puppets of Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The two countries say they have legitimate security interests
in Congo and accuse Kabila of failing to rid their common border
of Rwandan and Ugandan rebels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
