<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GA President Urges Joint Efforts for Food Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 20 (Xinhua) -- The president of the
53rd General Assembly (GA) session, Didier Opertti, Tuesday called
for joint efforts for both household and national food security.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a meeting marking the World Food Day, which falls on
October 16 each year, Opertti said, "What is needed therefore is
for the the various sectors of society: governments,
parliamentarians, NGOs, the media, scientists, educators, the
private sector, women and youths organizations and all others to
coordinate their efforts to achieve a greater synergy to work
collectively towards their household and national food security."
</P>
<P>
"During these times, in particular, when the financial and
trade markets are so volatile and vulnerable, producing negative
social effects, ensuring food security for the most vulnerable in
our societies becomes an urgent imperative and a priority," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In World Food Day observance, "we are provided with an
opportunity to examine our collective conscience as a world
community and admit that the death of 30,000 people from hunger
and malnutrition each day -- is morally and socially
unacceptable," he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Day was observed in some 150 countries on
October 16 on the theme "Women Feed the World," stressing women's
key role in food assessment by the United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization (FAO), which showed that 30 developing
countries are facing food emergencies, mainly due to the effect of
both El Nino and La Nina weather phenomena.
</P>
<P>
This year's theme is truly most appropriate as women,
particularly in the developing countries, produce half of the food
grown today, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Women provide a substantial contribution through their
multiple and varied roles in agriculture, such as growing,
processing and selling food crops, raising livestocks, fishing in
lakes and rivers, and harvesting forest resources, apart from
their roles in preparing food and nurturing the family," he added.
</P>
<P>
In his October 16 message to this year's World Food Day, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said, "Every year, World Food Day
reminds us of a tragic reality -- that the war against hunger and
malnutrition is still being fought."
</P>
<P>
In 1980, the General Assembly called for the observance of the
World Food Day for the first time on October 16, 1981 and annually
thereafter to heighten public awareness of the problem of hunger
in the world and to encourage attention to food production.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981021.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-21 </DATE_TIME>
