<HEADLINE> 17 Killed, Two Missing in Southern U.S. Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 20 (Xinhua) -- At least 17 people were
killed and two others missing in Texas flooding that was triggered
by torrential rains during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The downpours that began Saturday flooded 60 counties, nearly
one-fourth of the state. More than 50 centimeters of rain were
recorded over the weekend in San Antonio, an unprecedented amount
in such a short period.
</P>
<P>
The Guadalupe River, just east of San Antonio, is usually about
45 meters across. It was about five kilometers wide in some areas
and rising Monday, forcing 1,400 people to shelters.
</P>
<P>
Early Tuesday, the Guadalupe crested at a record 14.9 meters in
Cuero, a town of 7,000 people 150 kilometers southeast of San
Antonio, and the water was on its way south.
</P>
<P>
Frightened residents told of the river climbing three meters in
just four hours, swamping neighborhoods and forcing hundreds of
people from their homes without a chance to salvage many
belongings.
</P>
<P>
The Guadalupe is just one of many waterways swollen by weekend
rains that swamped central and southern Texas.
</P>
<P>
In DeWitt County, 1,200 people remained in shelters Tuesday
morning while emergency crews in boats floated through soaked
Cuero neighborhoods, rescuing residents.
</P>
<P>
Officials were considering evacuating about 1,300 inmates from
the Stevenson Unit prison near Cuero because of the flooding.
</P>
<P>
While houses were floating away in Cuero, up to 5,000 cattle
were roaming free in Caldwell County, northeast of San Antonio.
Thousands of animals were set loose when the flooded San Marcos
River washed away pens, barns and fencing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
