<HEADLINE> Security in Kampala Under Control: Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Security in Uganda's capital city
has been improved and it has been under strict control of the
police, a senior police commander told Xinhua Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Benjamin Namanya, the Police Supterintendent of Kampala Region
Extra, appealed to the general public to contribute to the security
of the environment in which they are living.
</P>
<P>
He talked about car robbery and theft, burglary, terrorism,
pick-pocketing and crimes by street children.
</P>
<P>
Four-wheel drive vehicles are most often the targets of car
robbers, he said, and the stolen vehicles are usually smuggled out
of the country.
</P>
<P>
Since September, two vehicles have been stolen and both are
recovered. More than three suspects have been arrested, he said,
adding that there are altogether 33 cars stolen so far this year and
23 of them recovered by the police.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the rest of the stolen vehicles are, I think, in the
high-walled homes," he said, "The stolen cars can be dumped in
somewhere or be still driven with fake registration numbers.
</P>
<P>
If the plate number of a car is different from its genuine number
which is often printed on the car body, the windscreen or rear mirror,
it is a suspicious car.
</P>
<P>
He also causioned people to take good care of the money they are
carrying. The loss of money is, more often than not, due to the
carelessness in carrying and keeping the money.
</P>
<P>
About 200 pick-pockets have been arrested since September, he
revealed. Four armed robbers have been killed in exchange of fire
with police in this period.
</P>
<P>
There are some cases of house burglary in Kampala, but most of
them happened in the suburbs of the city, the police officer said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the new wave of terrorism in the city, the
police commander assured that the police will do all they can to
detect and remove the potential dangers.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the public should be more careful and more
cooperative with the police. If there is anything suspicious, do not
hesitate to report to the nearest police, he advised.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of street children, he said that there is no immediate
solution to the problem of street children. It is difficult to
deal with street children as far as street crimes are
concerned, Namanya added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
