<HEADLINE> UNFPA Regrets Over U.S. Fund Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 20 (Xinhua) -- Nafis Sadik, executive
director of the United Nations Population Fund (UNFPA), on Tuesday
issued a statement, saying that the U.N. agency "deeply regrets"
the news that the United States will not include the funding for
UNFPA in appropriation for the coming financial year.
</P>
<P>
"The decision penalizes not only UNFPA but the millions of
ordinary women and men on whose behalf we work," the statement
said, "It will inevitably reduce our ability to implement vital
programs in the area of reproductive health and rights."
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. decision will mean the unnecessary death and
suffering of women who are deprived of the information and means
to plan their families," the statement said, "It will deny many
people in developing countries the right that Americans take
for granted -- the right to individual freedom in regard to the
size and spacing of the family."
</P>
<P>
It will weaken not only population programs but programs aimed
at better health, equal access to health and education for women,
and economic security, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. decision will hit especially hard the least developed
countries in Africa and elsewhere whose population programs are
most dependent on external assistance," the statement said, "It
will contribute to the spread of sexually transmitted diseases,
including HIV/AIDS, which pose an even-larger threat to health,
life and prospects for development."
</P>
<P>
"It is a step backwards from United States leadership in the
population field and United States support for
internationally-agreed approaches to population problems," it said.
</P>
<P>
Falling birth and population growth rates in developing
countries demonstrate beyond question the practical validity of
promoting reproductive health and rights as ends in themselves, as
well as the means to achieve smaller family and slower population
growth, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The decision to deny U.S. funding to UNFPA is also misguided
from the point of view of all those who, like UNFPA, wish to
promote reproductive health and rights in China," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
"The new UNFPA program in China, which is limited to 32
counties, was carefully designed to ensure respect for human
rights norms agreed by 180 nations at the International Conference
on Population and Development in 1994, including the vital
principle of individual decision on the size and spacing of the
family," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. funding for UNFPA is 20 million U.S. dollars in the fiscal
year 1998. The total approved by the United States for UNFPA in
the fiscal year 1988 was 25 million U.S. dollars, which was
reduced by 5 million U.S. dollars the amount expected to be spent
in China.
</P>
<P>
Since 1984, no U.S. funds have been available for UNFPA
expenditure in China. U.S. funding for UNFPA was suspended in 1986
when its total pledge was 46 million U.S. dollars, and was
restored by U.S. President Bill Clinton in 1993. UNFPA's total
resources in 1997 were 290 million U.S. dollars, according to
the statement.
</P>
<P>
In one year alone, the impact of the United States decision
to withdraw funding from UNFPA will be to deprive 870,000 women
of effective modern contraception. More than 520,000 will end up
not using any method.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
